} Bg7 {Now White's main move is 5.Nf3 by far. It makes a lot of sense to
develop the Knight to its natural square before doing anything else. White may
deviate from these main lines on move 5 with ideas like 5.Bd3 or 5.a3 , but
these options are not so relevant in the context of this Short & Sweet. They
have their points but are not immediately threatening to blow you out of the
water, as the general concept of ...Nc6 and ...e5 is the same as in the main
lines after 5.Nf3 . We'll have a look at 5.e5 , though. This move requires a
precise response, otherwise Black is in trouble.} 5. Nf3 {White speeds up the
Kingside development, which is the main move by a mile.} O-O 6. Be3 {In this
line, we deal with an important deviation from the mainline 6.Bd3 . White
plays 6.Be3 which develops the dark-squared Bishop first. The move has got
several advantages: 1 White strengthens his control over the d4-square. 2
White is just two moves away from castling Queenside 3 White makes it more
difficult for Black to push ...c5. But there must be some disadvantage, as
otherwise, the whole world would prefer to play Be3 right? On the downside,
there is: 1 White's e4-square is not supported by Bd3. In some variations, we
might try to exploit this weakness. 2 White is not able to castle Kingside on
the next move. Black's King is already in safety, whereas White's King does
not feel comfortable in the centre of the board. 3 The e3-Bishop is quite
vulnerable at the moment. It's unprotected, and we can attack it by playing ...
Ng4 under the right circumstances. Let's think about our strategic options.
Aiming for the ...e5-break is quite difficult. The immediate 6...e5 leads to
an advantage for White after 7.dxe5 dxe5 8.Qxd8 Rxd8 9.fxe5 Ng4 10.Bg5 .
Preparing the e5-push with 6...Nc6 is also not that attractive. Our c6-Knight
attacks e5 and d4, but both squares are firmly under White's control. He might
try to punish us immediately by playing 7.e5 . In the resulting position, we
lack the ...c5-break because our Knight on c6 is blocking the c-pawn. OK,
let's forget about playing e7-e5 for the time being. We have another option!}
b6 {We go for the ...c5-pawn push, instead of the ...e5-break. The immediate 6.
..c5 fails, so we need to invest a tempo in preparing the move. Furthermore,
we can put more pressure on e4, a pawn that is quite vulnerable at the moment,
by playing ...Bb7 next. After 6...b6 we will frequently meet a particular pawn
formation. Often White will play e4-e5 while we push c7-c5. This formation is
called 'Diamond formation' due to all pawns between the a-file and e-file
being on dark squares. It indeed looks like a crystal or even a diamond.
Creative names like that are fun and even help to visualize and memorize ideas.
} 7. Qd2 {White prepares Queenside castling.} Bb7 {We develop our Bishop and
attack e4 a second time. It is a very natural move that looks fine to us, but
7...c5 is an alternative that has been tested, as well.} 8. e5 {The main move.
White's e4 pawn is under fire, and he pushes it forward.} Ng4 {We could play 8.
..dxe5 but keeping the tension and playing ...c5 first looks more attractive.
We aim for the so-called 'Diamond formation', as discussed earlier in this
variation.} 9. O-O-O {Likely the best way for White to try to fight for an
advantage.} c5 {Again we reach the 'Diamond formation'. This time we are even
prepared to sacrifice a pawn for active piece play.} 10. dxc5 {Played almost
exclusively by White in this position. Grabbing the pawn is the most
principled decision, for sure.} bxc5 11. Bxc5 {White grabs the pawn.} Qa5 {We
regard this as the best move in the position. The alternatives are 11...Qc7 or
11...Nd7 , but we like to focus on our Queenside counterplay and want to
involve the Queen quickly.} 12. Ba3 dxe5 13. Nd5 {White wants to simplify the
position and offers a Queen's trade. A fun trick to keep in mind is 13.h3 Bh6!
which is very annoying for White.} Qxd2+ {It does not make a difference if you
take on d5 with the Queen. It's just a transposition of moves. On d2, we can
shout 'check!' ... at least in online play, there is no arbiter to punish us
for it!} 14. Rxd2 Bxd5 15. Rxd5 {The last moves were more or less forced.} Ne3
{We keep White busy, forking White's Rook and the f1-Bishop.} 16. Rd2 {This
position has been on the board several times, even at the highest level. Two
top GMs, Kasimdzhanov and Svidler, drew their game in a FIDE World
Championship event when Black played 16...Nc6 .} Bh6 {We recommend playing 16..
.Bh6 . The vis-a-vis of the h6-Bishop and White's pieces on d2 on c1 are quite
annoying for White. Although we are heading to an endgame, the game is still
quite complicated and rich. We just give a sample line to show an important
idea. After 17.Bxe7 Nxf1! 18.Bxf8 Bxf4 19.Rxf1 Kxf8 White has no advantage. It
is still quite interesting to play, though. The non-symmetrical majorities are
always spicing the game up, even deep into the endgame.} *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Short & Sweet"]
[Black "Austrian Attack (4.f4) #4"]
[Result "*"]
[PlyCount "32"]

1. e4 d6 {This is the starting move of the Pirc Defense. We open the c8-h3
diagonal for our light-squared Bishop, but this is not the primary purpose of
that move. By playing 1...d6 we stop White from pushing e4-e5 for the time
being. We plan to develop our Kingside by fianchettoing the dark-squared
Bishop with ...g6 and ...Bg7. The Knight usually jumps to f6, and we are ready
to castle Kingside quickly.} 2. d4 {White occupies the centre with the perfect
pawn duo on e4 and d4, a very natural move. White occasionally plays without
d4, for example by playing 2.Nc3 or 2.Bc4 . Black's Pirc setup with ...g6, ...
Bg7 and ...O-O is a good answer to these offbeat lines, too.} Nf6 {The Knight
immediately attacks the e4-pawn. This reduces White's options, compared to
playing 2...g6 or the similar @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/
RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@ 1.e4 g6 2.d4 Bg7 , which allows White to play
3.c4 amongst others. After 2...Nf6 , White's overwhelming main move is 3.Nc3
on which we will focus in the Short & Sweet.} 3. Nc3 g6 {After 3...g6 we have
reached the starting position of the Pirc Defense.} 4. f4 {This is the
starting move of the Austrian Attack. White builds a broad pawn centre and
often tries to attack the Kingside later. The f-pawn supports the pawn advance
e4-e5, which is the most critical idea available for White. A supported pawn
on e5 will seriously hamper our strong g7-Bishop, which is why fighting this
idea is a crucial element of Black's strategy. The Austrian Attack has always
been regarded as the mainline of the Pirc and remains very popular on all
levels. A very understandable statistic, as White's play is aggressive and
very straightforward. The direct nature of White's strategy, however, is also
helping Black to some extent. With 4.f4 , White immediately commits to a
central structure, so we know what to deal with straight away. The game's
direction is not as apparent against after a more flexible move like 4.Be3
when White might still play f4 later, but may also play with f2-f3 or Nf3,
depending on Black's setup. The consequence is that the lines after 4.f4 are
less ridden with transpositions and more forcing. Let's talk a bit about the
various lines. A. The most popular branch is 4.f4 Bg7 5.Nf3 O-O 6.Bd3 which we
answer with 6...Nc6 , aiming for ...e5. B. Instead of 6.Bd3 as in A above,
White may also play @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pp1p/3p1np1/8/3PP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/
R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@ 4.f4 Bg7 5.Nf3 O-O 6.Be3 which hints at a
possible Queenside castling. C. After @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pp1p/3p1np1/8/
3PP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@ 4.f4 Bg7 5.Nf3 O-O White also
has the aggressive option 6.e5 One crucial point: at various moments White has
the option to play e4-e5, aggressively advancing in the centre. It is not
possible to fight these lines with the same approach each time. You need to
look at each one and learn and play the best reply, as the small differences
matter a lot. The Austrian Attack is probably the part of the Pirc that
demands the most memorization; there is no way to avoid that. White's play is
rather concrete and aggressive, and our responses need to be precise. In
slower lines, like the Classical Variation @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pp1p/
3p1np1/8/3PP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@ 4.Nf3 Bg7 5.Be2 or
@@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pp1p/3p1np1/8/3PP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0
4@@EndFEN@@ 4.g3 Black can get away with knowing only some concrete lines and
ideas. If you try to fight the Austrian Attack with vague ideas, you might
just get destroyed. The upside is: if you know what to do, you'll be fine. In
the Short & Sweet, we'll focus on the most important lines that you'll
encounter in your games or that demand a precise response that you should know.
} Bg7 {Now White's main move is 5.Nf3 by far. It makes a lot of sense to
develop the Knight to its natural square before doing anything else. White may
deviate from these main lines on move 5 with ideas like 5.Bd3 or 5.a3 , but
these options are not so relevant in the context of this Short & Sweet. They
have their points but are not immediately threatening to blow you out of the
water, as the general concept of ...Nc6 and ...e5 is the same as in the main
lines after 5.Nf3 . We'll have a look at 5.e5 , though. This move requires a
precise response, otherwise Black is in trouble.} 5. Nf3 {White speeds up the
Kingside development, which is the main move by a mile.} O-O 6. Be3 {In this
line, we deal with an important deviation from the mainline 6.Bd3 . White
plays 6.Be3 which develops the dark-squared Bishop first. The move has got
several advantages: 1 White strengthens his control over the d4-square. 2
White is just two moves away from castling Queenside 3 White makes it more
difficult for Black to push ...c5. But there must be some disadvantage, as
otherwise, the whole world would prefer to play Be3 right? On the downside,
there is: 1 White's e4-square is not supported by Bd3. In some variations, we
might try to exploit this weakness. 2 White is not able to castle Kingside on
the next move. Black's King is already in safety, whereas White's King does
not feel comfortable in the centre of the board. 3 The e3-Bishop is quite
vulnerable at the moment. It's unprotected, and we can attack it by playing ...
Ng4 under the right circumstances. Let's think about our strategic options.
Aiming for the ...e5-break is quite difficult. The immediate 6...e5 leads to
an advantage for White after 7.dxe5 dxe5 8.Qxd8 Rxd8 9.fxe5 Ng4 10.Bg5 .
Preparing the e5-push with 6...Nc6 is also not that attractive. Our c6-Knight
attacks e5 and d4, but both squares are firmly under White's control. He might
try to punish us immediately by playing 7.e5 . In the resulting position, we
lack the ...c5-break because our Knight on c6 is blocking the c-pawn. OK,
let's forget about playing e7-e5 for the time being. We have another option!}
b6 {We go for the ...c5-pawn push, instead of the ...e5-break. The immediate 6.
..c5 fails, so we need to invest a tempo in preparing the move. Furthermore,
we can put more pressure on e4, a pawn that is quite vulnerable at the moment,
by playing ...Bb7 next. After 6...b6 we will frequently meet a particular pawn
formation. Often White will play e4-e5 while we push c7-c5. This formation is
called 'Diamond formation' due to all pawns between the a-file and e-file
being on dark squares. It indeed looks like a crystal or even a diamond.
Creative names like that are fun and even help to visualize and memorize ideas.
} 7. e5 {White plays aggressively and pushes his e-pawn. The move is
recommended by Chris Baker in 'A Startling Chess Opening Repertoire'.} Ng4 {We
attack the unprotected Bishop on e3 and gain some time.} 8. Bg1 {White wants
to keep his dark-squared Bishop. On the one hand, the Bishop is needed to
control the dark squares and support the centre. On the other hand, White
intends to play h3 soon, pushing the Black Knight to a less ideas square on h6.
} c5 {We reach the diamond structure, which we outlined earlier. White's
centre is under severe pressure now.} 9. h3 Nh6 {White has played aggressively,
but the advanced pawn centre is already under heavy fire. One general problem
is the Bishop on g1. It is difficult for White to move it back to e3, as we
would jump with our Knight to f5 and kick the Bishop again.} 10. d5 {White
wants to keep his centre and gain even more space. After 10.dxc5? we can play
10...bxc5! as 11.Qd5 Qb6 is fine for Black. White can't play 12.Qxa8? due to
12...Bb7 trapping the Queen.} Bb7 11. Bc4 {This move was suggested by Baker,
who likes White's chances. We agree that the position is quite sharp, and
White benefits from more space. But Black's setup is very dynamic. It has a
coiled spring quality, with lots of energy ready to be released with great
effect.} Nd7 {You may also insert 11...a6 12.a4 first and then play 12...Nd7 .
We like Black's chances and like to point out an instructive idea.} 12. Qe2 a6
13. a4 b5 {The coiled spring!} 14. axb5 axb5 15. Rxa8 Qxa8 16. Bxb5 Nb6 {Black
is somewhat better, in our view. We can penetrate on a1 with our Queen and
White's d5-pawn is weak, as well. White's position is overextended and tough
to play.} *

