@@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pp1p/3p1np1/8/3PP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0
4@@EndFEN@@ 4.g3 Black can get away with knowing only some concrete lines and
ideas. If you try to fight the Austrian Attack with vague ideas, you might
just get destroyed. The upside is: if you know what to do, you'll be fine. In
the Short & Sweet, we'll focus on the most important lines that you'll
encounter in your games or that demand a precise response that you should know.
} Bg7 {Now White's main move is 5.Nf3 by far. It makes a lot of sense to
develop the Knight to its natural square before doing anything else. White may
deviate from these main lines on move 5 with ideas like 5.Bd3 or 5.a3 , but
these options are not so relevant in the context of this Short & Sweet. They
have their points but are not immediately threatening to blow you out of the
water, as the general concept of ...Nc6 and ...e5 is the same as in the main
lines after 5.Nf3 . We'll have a look at 5.e5 , though. This move requires a
precise response, otherwise Black is in trouble.} 5. Nf3 {White speeds up the
Kingside development, which is the main move by a mile.} O-O 6. e5 {The pawn
push e4-e5 is quite aggressive and scores rather well for White. The game is
often concrete, and White does not need to bother with the many alternatives
Black has in the mainline after 6.Bd3 . We need to be careful and learn some
details by heart. First decision: to take or not to take on e5?} dxe5 {We
recommend taking the pawn in the centre. In comparison, after the main move
@@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/ppp1ppbp/3p1np1/8/3PPP2/2N2N2/PPP3PP/R1BQKB1R w KQ - 3
6@@EndFEN@@ 6.Bd3 Nc6 White also has the option to play 7.e5 , which we
capture as well. However, if White plays e5 one move earlier, the situation is
different. After @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pp1p/3p1np1/8/3PP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/
R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@ 4.f4 Bg7 5.e5 we recommend 5...Nfd7! which is
stronger than taking. So, as a rule of thumb: you take on e5 AFTER you have
castled, while against the early e4-e5 you play ...Nfd7. The reasoning is
quite logical: with ...O-O being played, White has the dangerous h4-h5 attack
available after the Knight retreat. While a line like @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/
ppp1ppbp/3p1np1/8/3PPP2/2N2N2/PPP3PP/R1BQKB1R w KQ - 3 6@@EndFEN@@ 6.e5 Nfd7 7.
h4 is not fatal, we feel that Black has a much easier job in practical play if
you take on e5. This is, in particular, true in faster time control games,
when the initiative is vital. You might struggle to remember a defensive
detail, fall behind on the clock, and get in trouble. Therefore we recommend
playing 6...dxe5 , after which White chooses between the two pawn recaptures.
The resulting play is completely different, as 7.dxe5 leads to a Queen trade,
while 7.fxe5 is a much more aggressive choice, aiming for an attack along the
f-file. In the 7.fxe5 line, you need to know some concrete ideas against
White's aggression, while 7.dxe5 is less dependent on knowledge. White's slow
approach should not be underestimated, but in the end, we are not unduly
worried about this line.} 7. fxe5 {This can be regarded as the main move.
Taking with the f-pawn keeps the Queens on the board and opens up the f-file
for the Rook. All nice and good, but Black is well developed, and we will soon
attack White's centre with ...c5. First of all, our Knight has a good spot to
jump to.} Nd5 {Our Knight occupies a strong position in the centre now. It is
no surprise that White's most popular move is 8.Bc4 now, directly attacking
our best piece. One important general point to address: From a strategic/
long-term point of view, our position is fine and maybe even preferable. With .
..c5 on the agenda, White's advanced centre will be under heavy fire. Is Black
better then? No, because there is a catch: the King's Knight often is the best
defender of the King, but this piece is now on d5 and will often take on c3,
like after 8.Bc4 Nxc3 . We lack this important defender and White's e5-pawn
and open f-file easily help to drum up an attack on our King. Imagine a setup
with Bc4, O-O and Qe1-h4: this is very scary, to say the least! The conclusion
is: we need to treat White's approach with some respect, otherwise we might
get hurt badly. As mentioned, 8.Bc4 is White's main move now.} 8. Bc4 {You can
expect this move to be played most of the time in this situation. White
develops a piece with tempo and places the Bishop on a natural diagonal,
looking at f7 and our King!} Nxc3 {Clearly the most principled move. We lose
no time with retreating and instead weaken White's structure.} 9. bxc3 c5 {We
need to fight against White's impressive pawn mass in the centre. White will
attack our kingside soon, and we need to start our counterplay immediately.}
10. O-O {This is the most natural move for White. After the Knight jump 10.Ng5
we should play 10...h6! immediately to force a decision of the Knight. This is
much better than 10...Nc6? when 11.O-O attacks our f7-pawn and we'd need to
play the undesirable move 11...e6 .} Bg4 {One of the most important moments in
this line! After the natural-looking 10...Nc6 White might play 11.Ng5!? to
avoid the pin. In comparison to @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/ppp1ppbp/6p1/4P3/2BP4/
2P2N2/P1P3PP/R1BQK2R b KQ - 0 9@@EndFEN@@ 9...c5 10.Ng5 there is additional
pressure on f7 due to the f1-Rook. We thus would not be able to play
@@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/pp2ppbp/2n3p1/2p1P1N1/2BP4/2P5/P1P3PP/R1BQ1RK1 b - - 3
11@@EndFEN@@ 11...h6 and would need to play 11...e6 , which is clearly not a
move you like to play. So what to do? Well, we have a multi-purpose move. We
can develop a piece and indirectly increase the pressure against the central
square d4 by pinning one of the White defenders. Our next move will be ...Nc6
in most cases, but the order of the two moves is of paramount importance!
After 10...Bg4! we take a look at White's most popular move 11.Be3} 11. Be3 {
This move looks natural and is played most often in this position. We get a
good position with natural moves, though. An idea worth knowing is that after
White's alternative 11.h3 Bxf3 12.Qxf3 we should play 12...Nc6 when it's no
problem to allow 13.Bxf7+ Kh8 , as our pressure on d4 is strong enough to win
back the pawn. Often White's Bishop on f7 is rather misplaced in this scenario.
} Nc6 {No rocket science: develop and put pressure on d4. The main nuance was
to play 10... Bg4 first, and only now ...Nc6. We think that White now runs the
risk of getting into trouble. The pawn structure is clearly an issue, and
there is no dangerous attack in sight.} 12. h3 Bxf3 13. Rxf3 {The main move.
White keeps his Queen on d1 to protect the d4-pawn.} Qa5 {We complete
development and already prefer Black slightly. White's centre is vulnerable
and his King is not safe with all the dark-squared weaknesses around him
@@StartBracket@@f2, g3 and h2@@EndBracket@@. We can continue with developing
Rad8 and put pressure along the d-file on White's pawn weakness d4. It should
be mentioned that 13...Rc8 is a fine alternative of about equal strength.} 14.
Bf2 {Or 14.Qf1 Qxc3 15.Rd1 Na5! which gives Black a much better position.} Rad8
{We have nice pressure on White's centre, especially the d4-pawn. Furthermore,
we don't have any weaknesses. Instead, White's pawn structure is shattered and
a long term worry for our opponent.} *

