water, as the general concept of ...Nc6 and ...e5 is the same as in the main
lines after 5.Nf3 . We'll have a look at 5.e5 , though. This move requires a
precise response, otherwise Black is in trouble.} 5. Nf3 {White speeds up the
Kingside development, which is the main move by a mile.} O-O 6. Bd3 Nc6 {We
develop our Queenside Knight to its most natural square in the opening. On c6,
the Knight takes a look at the dark central squares d4 and e5. In some cases,
it can also jump to b4, attacking White's light-squared Bishop. After 6...Nc6
White's main moves are 7.e5 and 7.O-O} 7. e5 {Pushing his e-pawn is White's
most aggressive move in the position and the most popular. White is scoring
quite well with it, but this is largely due to Black making a key mistake
early on. We recommend taking on e5 similarly to the line @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/
ppp1pp1p/3p1np1/8/3PP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@ 4.f4 Bg7 5.
Nf3 O-O 6.e5 when 6...dxe5 is our move, too. So, after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/
ppp1pp1p/3p1np1/8/3PP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@ 4.f4 Bg7 5.
Nf3 O-O 6.Bd3 Nc6 7.e5 dxe5 8.fxe5 comes the key moment mentioned. Here only
the less obvious move 8...Nh5! does the job - White's overall plus score after
7.e5 results from Black not knowing this detail. If we are well prepared in
this line, we don't need to be afraid of 7.e5 . The reasoning behind 8...Nh5
is explained in the notes to the move. Of course, White has the less critical
@@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/ppp1ppbp/2n2np1/4p3/3P1P2/2NB1N2/PPP3PP/R1BQK2R w KQ - 0
8@@EndFEN@@ 8.dxe5 but this is rather easily met with little concrete
knowledge necessary. Let's have a look.} dxe5 {White attacks our Knight, and
we need to react. We need to compare this line to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/
ppp1pp1p/3p1np1/8/3PP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@ 4.f4 Bg7 5.
Nf3 O-O 6.e5 . In this variation, we suggest playing 6...dxe5 , and we
recommend answering @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/ppp1ppbp/3p1np1/8/3PPP2/2N2N2/PPP3PP/
R1BQKB1R w KQ - 3 6@@EndFEN@@ 6.Bd3 Nc6 7.e5 in the same way. Against
@@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/ppp1ppbp/3p1np1/8/3PPP2/2N2N2/PPP3PP/R1BQKB1R w KQ - 3
6@@EndFEN@@ 6.e5 , Black has the interesting alternative 6...Nfd7 , intending
to play a quick ...c5 to attack the centre. This idea is not available here,
which makes @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/ppp1ppbp/3p1np1/8/3PPP2/2N2N2/PPP3PP/R1BQKB1R
w KQ - 3 6@@EndFEN@@ 6.Bd3 Nc6 7.e5 dxe5 more or less the only good move.
Black has experimented with other ideas but without much success. After the
capture, White's decision between 8.dxe5 and 8.fxe5 is, unsurprisingly,
fundamental for the further course of the game.} 8. fxe5 {This move is more
aggressive than 8.dxe5 . White keeps two centre pawns and opens up the f-file,
which he might use for an attack. The Bishop on c1 gains more scope, as well.
For Black, the correct answer to 8.fxe5 is the most important point to
remember in this part of the Austrian Attack!} Nh5 {This is probably the most
important moment in the whole 7.e5 variation. White's recapture 8.fxe5 is the
most popular and the one you will face regularly. It is important to
understand the difference between these two lines: A. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/
ppp1pp1p/3p1np1/8/3PP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@ 4.f4 Bg7 5.
Nf3 O-O 6.e5 dxe5 7.fxe5 Nd5! B. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pp1p/3p1np1/8/3PP3/
2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@ 4.f4 Bg7 5.Nf3 O-O 6.Bd3 Nc6 7.e5
dxe5 8.fxe5 Nh5! The key difference is that in line A we don't have ...Nc6
played, which means that we have ...c5 to quickly attack White's centre. This
is illustrated by the main continuation @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/ppp1ppbp/6p1/3nP3/
3P4/2N2N2/PPP3PP/R1BQKB1R w KQ - 1 8@@EndFEN@@ 8.Bc4 Nxc3 9.bxc3 c5! or the
crude 8.h4?! c5! , when White is already in trouble. Now, in line B, the one
examined here, the situation is different. After @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/ppp1ppbp/
2n2np1/4P3/3P4/2NB1N2/PPP3PP/R1BQK2R b KQ - 0 8@@EndFEN@@ 8...Nd5? 9.Nxd5 Qxd5
10.c3 White has a solid centre and is ready for an attack on the Kingside. We
badly lack counterplay against d4, and the Knight on c6 is misplaced. After
the less intuitive 8...Nh5 , White needs to take care of his d4-pawn now. They
can either protect it directly, by playing 9.Be3 or indirectly with his Queen
by retreating the d3-Bishop to e2. In most cases, however, this is just a
transposition of moves and both lead to the same position at the end. In any
case, our setup includes ...Bg4 to complete development and a quick ...f7-f6
to attack White's centre. This will also give the Knight on h5 a more useful
role.} 9. Be3 {The alternative 9.Be2 would most likely lead to the main
variation after 9...Bg4 10.Be3 as the pressure on d4 leaves White little
choice.} Bg4 10. Be2 f6 {The move ...f6! is a key idea to remember. We attack
White's centre and force a concession. White is not able to keep his pawn on
e5 anymore, and will most likely capture on f6.} 11. exf6 {This is played most
of the time. All recaptures lead to a playable position, but we recommend
taking with the e-pawn. This is the soundest option in terms of pawn structure
and looks fully satisfactory for Black. Instead of 11.exf6 White also has 11.
e6?! , but this is dubious due to 11...f5! when the pawn on e6 is doomed in
the long run.} exf6 {We like this move the most, keeping the pawn structure
sound.} 12. O-O {White decides to castle Kingside, which is played most often.}
Re8 {Black could play 12...f5 13.Qd2 Qd6 leading to an unclear position. We
recommend playing 12...Re8 , though. We think this move is more precise, as it
allows the strong idea ...Nc6-e7-f5} 13. Qd2 Ne7 {We have reached an
interesting position. Black has nice piece play and chances to exploit the
dark-squared weaknesses in White's camp. The ...Nf5-idea may even be followed
up by ...Bh6, if possible.} 14. Bc4+ Kh8 {We like Black's position, because it
already seems a bit easier for us to play. For example after the natural move
15.h3?! Nf5! White can't play 16.Bf2 to keep his Bishop. We would play 16...
Bxf3 followed by ...Bh6 and a great position. The highest level game that
reached this position was played between S. Karjakin and G. Jones in Bilbao
2014. The later World Championship challenger went for 15.Nh4 but this can't
bother Black much. Gawain Jones was fine after 15...Nc6 16.Bf2 Ne5!? but Black
has some fine alternatives in 15...f5 or even 15...g5!? , which looks a bit
loose, admittedly. We don't see any problems for Black in this line, and even
the most respected expert on the Austrian Attack, Sergey Karjakin, didn't find
a way forward.} *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Short & Sweet"]
[Black "Austrian Attack (4.f4) #7"]
[Result "*"]
[PlyCount "26"]

1. e4 d6 {This is the starting move of the Pirc Defense. We open the c8-h3
diagonal for our light-squared Bishop, but this is not the primary purpose of
that move. By playing 1...d6 we stop White from pushing e4-e5 for the time
being. We plan to develop our Kingside by fianchettoing the dark-squared
Bishop with ...g6 and ...Bg7. The Knight usually jumps to f6, and we are ready
to castle Kingside quickly.} 2. d4 {White occupies the centre with the perfect
pawn duo on e4 and d4, a very natural move. White occasionally plays without
d4, for example by playing 2.Nc3 or 2.Bc4 . Black's Pirc setup with ...g6, ...
Bg7 and ...O-O is a good answer to these offbeat lines, too.} Nf6 {The Knight
immediately attacks the e4-pawn. This reduces White's options, compared to
playing 2...g6 or the similar @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/
RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@ 1.e4 g6 2.d4 Bg7 , which allows White to play
3.c4 amongst others. After 2...Nf6 , White's overwhelming main move is 3.Nc3
on which we will focus in the Short & Sweet.} 3. Nc3 g6 {After 3...g6 we have
reached the starting position of the Pirc Defense.} 4. f4 {This is the
starting move of the Austrian Attack. White builds a broad pawn centre and
often tries to attack the Kingside later. The f-pawn supports the pawn advance
e4-e5, which is the most critical idea available for White. A supported pawn
on e5 will seriously hamper our strong g7-Bishop, which is why fighting this
idea is a crucial element of Black's strategy. The Austrian Attack has always
been regarded as the mainline of the Pirc and remains very popular on all
levels. A very understandable statistic, as White's play is aggressive and
very straightforward. The direct nature of White's strategy, however, is also
helping Black to some extent. With 4.f4 , White immediately commits to a
central structure, so we know what to deal with straight away. The game's
direction is not as apparent against after a more flexible move like 4.Be3
when White might still play f4 later, but may also play with f2-f3 or Nf3,
depending on Black's setup. The consequence is that the lines after 4.f4 are
less ridden with transpositions and more forcing. Let's talk a bit about the
various lines. A. The most popular branch is 4.f4 Bg7 5.Nf3 O-O 6.Bd3 which we
answer with 6...Nc6 , aiming for ...e5. B. Instead of 6.Bd3 as in A above,
White may also play @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pp1p/3p1np1/8/3PP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/
R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@ 4.f4 Bg7 5.Nf3 O-O 6.Be3 which hints at a
possible Queenside castling. C. After @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pp1p/3p1np1/8/
3PP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@ 4.f4 Bg7 5.Nf3 O-O White also
has the aggressive option 6.e5 One crucial point: at various moments White has
the option to play e4-e5, aggressively advancing in the centre. It is not
possible to fight these lines with the same approach each time. You need to
look at each one and learn and play the best reply, as the small differences
matter a lot. The Austrian Attack is probably the part of the Pirc that
demands the most memorization; there is no way to avoid that. White's play is
rather concrete and aggressive, and our responses need to be precise. In
slower lines, like the Classical Variation @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pp1p/
3p1np1/8/3PP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@ 4.Nf3 Bg7 5.Be2 or
@@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pp1p/3p1np1/8/3PP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0
4@@EndFEN@@ 4.g3 Black can get away with knowing only some concrete lines and
ideas. If you try to fight the Austrian Attack with vague ideas, you might
just get destroyed. The upside is: if you know what to do, you'll be fine. In
the Short & Sweet, we'll focus on the most important lines that you'll
encounter in your games or that demand a precise response that you should know.
} Bg7 {Now White's main move is 5.Nf3 by far. It makes a lot of sense to
develop the Knight to its natural square before doing anything else. White may
deviate from these main lines on move 5 with ideas like 5.Bd3 or 5.a3 , but
these options are not so relevant in the context of this Short & Sweet. They
have their points but are not immediately threatening to blow you out of the
water, as the general concept of ...Nc6 and ...e5 is the same as in the main
lines after 5.Nf3 . We'll have a look at 5.e5 , though. This move requires a
precise response, otherwise Black is in trouble.} 5. Nf3 {White speeds up the
Kingside development, which is the main move by a mile.} O-O 6. Bd3 Nc6 {We
develop our Queenside Knight to its most natural square in the opening. On c6,
the Knight takes a look at the dark central squares d4 and e5. In some cases,
it can also jump to b4, attacking White's light-squared Bishop. After 6...Nc6
White's main moves are 7.e5 and 7.O-O} 7. d5 {White is aggressive and wants to
punish us for our Knight move, forcing us to move it again. This is a
short-term success for White, but there is a long-term issue. We gain
something in return: our g7-Bishop enjoys the open, long diagonal a1-h8
without any central pawns obstructing the view.} Nb4 {We can play this active
move and exploit the placement of White's light-squared Bishop. White does not
want to allow ...Nxd3 and needs to lose some time in return.} 8. Be2 {White
also has 8.Bc4 , but we can answer it in the same fashion as 8.Be2 .} c6 {It's
actually easier to attack a pawn on d5 than a pawn on d4 - this is a drawback
of White's 7. d5.} 9. a3 Na6 10. Bxa6 {We don't need to worry about this
capture, quite the opposite. We need to recapture with the b-pawn, which
results in a doubled pawn on the a-file. However, in return, we gain the
Bishop-pair and a semi-open b-file. This is far more important than the pawn
structure. Instead of 10.Bxa6? White should develop with 10.Be3 when 10...Nc7
leads to a position with equal chances. An idea for Black is to play ...cxd5
next, followed by ...b6 and ...Bb7.} bxa6 11. dxc6 {Greedy and bad! White
should play a more reasonable move instead, like 11.Be3 after 11...Qc7
@@StartBracket@@amongst others@@EndBracket@@ Black is better, but White can
still fight.} Qb6 {We'd like to get the pawn back and don't need to be afraid
of 12.Nd5} 12. Nd5 Nxd5 13. exd5 {White has covered the c6-pawn, but Chess is
still about checkmating the opponent's King! White still has the King on e1,
which allows a strong attack that can now be started with many moves.} Re8 {We
suggest this one, aiming to open up the e-file as soon as possible. Black is
much better after some other moves, too. For example, 13...Qc5 or 13...Bf5
leads to a large advantage, too. After 13...Re8 we don't see a good move for
White. Stockfish suggests as the best line for White: 14.Qe2 Qa5+ 15.c3 Qxd5
16.O-O Qxc6 - this way, White avoided getting mated in the centre but is just
a pawn down and completely busted.} *

