encounter in your games or that demand a precise response that you should know.
} Bg7 {Now White's main move is 5.Nf3 by far. It makes a lot of sense to
develop the Knight to its natural square before doing anything else. White may
deviate from these main lines on move 5 with ideas like 5.Bd3 or 5.a3 , but
these options are not so relevant in the context of this Short & Sweet. They
have their points but are not immediately threatening to blow you out of the
water, as the general concept of ...Nc6 and ...e5 is the same as in the main
lines after 5.Nf3 . We'll have a look at 5.e5 , though. This move requires a
precise response, otherwise Black is in trouble.} 5. Nf3 {White speeds up the
Kingside development, which is the main move by a mile.} O-O 6. Bd3 Nc6 {We
develop our Queenside Knight to its most natural square in the opening. On c6,
the Knight takes a look at the dark central squares d4 and e5. In some cases,
it can also jump to b4, attacking White's light-squared Bishop. After 6...Nc6
White's main moves are 7.e5 and 7.O-O} 7. O-O {This natural move is one of two
mainlines for White. White wants to bring the King into a safer position
before committing to more concrete action. White's main alternative is the
move 7.e5 which we examine in the Short & Sweet, too.} e5 {the immediate
action 7...e5 in the centre is possible and good. We quickly provoke a crisis
in the centre and force White to decide between various possible pawn
formations. White's main answers are the captures 8.fxe5 and 8.dxe5} 8. fxe5 {
White opens up the f-file for the Rook. Instead 8.dxe5 dxe5 9.f5 is also
possible, but less popular. 9...Nb4 is a good reply to this line.} dxe5 9. d5 {
White grabs space in the centre. It is the only testing move. After 9.dxe5
Nxe5! 10.Nxe5 Qd4+ 11.Kh1 Qxe5 12.Bf4 Qc5 Black is in good shape.} Ne7 {Here
Black has the fine alternative 9...Nd4 . It was tough to decide between the
two Knight moves, but we decided to go for 9...Ne7 . The reason is that it
leads to more lively play than 9...Nd4 . A drawback of 9...Nd4 is the main
reply 10.Nxe5 when Black has to regain the pawn with 10...Nxe4 or 10...Nxd5 .
These lines are fine but lead to simplifications and are less combative. For
sure, you may add 9...Nd4 to your repertoire if you like to have a solid
alternative, but we'd like to make a case for 9...Ne7 in this course. Our idea
is to attack White's centre with ...c6 on the next move, pretty much
regardless of White's choice.} 10. Nxe5 {That's the first move White players
usually consider, and in most cases, they go for it. An interesting
alternative is 10.Qe1 , when we play 10...c6 , too.} c6 {It is important to
avoid 10...Nfxd5 . After 11.Nxd5 Nxd5 12.Nxf7 White secures an advantage. Our
suggestion is much stronger and gives Black good chances. White's main reply
to 10...c6 is 11.Bg5 but we check some alternatives in the full course, too.}
11. Bg5 {This is White's main move by far. It looks logical to develop a piece
on an active square and attack the Knight at the same time. Of course White
needs to avoid 11.dxc6?? Qd4+ , blundering a piece.} cxd5 {We are happy to
destroy White's centre. Wait! Aren't we losing the Knight on f6 now?} 12. Bxf6
{This must be critical. Instead, 12.exd5 Nexd5 is just fine for Black. We are
well centralized and have no weaknesses. On the other hand, you need to
consider that White lacks the f-pawn, which makes the King less secure for the
rest of the game.} Qb6+ {This the tactical justification, regaining the piece.}
13. Kh1 Bxf6 14. Nxd5 {White's best move in the position. Instead 14.Ng4?! Bg7
15.Nxd5 Nxd5 16.exd5 Qd4! leads to an advantage for Black. We'll restore
material equality and enjoy a monster Bishop-pair.} Nxd5 15. Nc4 {What a mess!
Our Queen, Knight, and f6-Bishop are all under fire. There is this famous
quote that our opponent can only take one piece at a time, and this applies
here, too. First of all, we need to move the Queen.} Qc5 {Black has two good
alternatives: 15...Qd4 and 15...Qd8 . We like to keep the Queen active, and on
d4, it might get a kick with c3 soon.} 16. exd5 Bg7 {Alright, let's keep the
VIP @@StartBracket@@Very Important Piece@@EndBracket@@.} 17. Qf3 {Almost
forced. White's d-pawn was attacked, and this is the only acceptable way to
cover it.} b6 {There is no right square for the Bishop on the diagonal c8-h3.
Therefore ...b6 suggests itself, with ...Bb7 or ...Ba6 next. Black is a pawn
down, but our Bishops are excellent pieces. It is rather difficult for White
to avoid returning a pawn, as d5 and b2 are under fire. A line like 18.c3 Bb7
19.Ne3 Rae8 20.Rae1 f5 sees White clinging to the pawn, but Black has all the
active ideas.} *

