1. e4 d6 {This is the starting move of the Pirc Defense. We open the c8-h3
diagonal for our light-squared Bishop, but this is not the primary purpose of
that move. By playing 1...d6 we stop White from pushing e4-e5 for the time
being. We plan to develop our Kingside by fianchettoing the dark-squared
Bishop with ...g6 and ...Bg7. The Knight usually jumps to f6, and we are ready
to castle Kingside quickly.} 2. d4 {White occupies the centre with the perfect
pawn duo on e4 and d4, a very natural move. White occasionally plays without
d4, for example by playing 2.Nc3 or 2.Bc4 . Black's Pirc setup with ...g6, ...
Bg7 and ...O-O is a good answer to these offbeat lines, too.} Nf6 {The Knight
immediately attacks the e4-pawn. This reduces White's options, compared to
playing 2...g6 or the similar @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/
RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@ 1.e4 g6 2.d4 Bg7 , which allows White to play
3.c4 amongst others. After 2...Nf6 , White's overwhelming main move is 3.Nc3
on which we will focus in the Short & Sweet.} 3. Nc3 g6 {After 3...g6 we have
reached the starting position of the Pirc Defense.} 4. Nf3 {White develops the
Knight to its most natural square and gets closer to Kingside castling. White
is not committed to castling Kingsides, obviously, but some more aggressive
setups involving the f-pawn are out of the picture. In comparison, after 4.Be3
White may still play f3 or f4, the pawn structure is not yet determined. After
4.Nf3 , we play the natural move 4...Bg7 , when White has a wide choice of
moves. We focus on the Classical Variation, which features 5.Be2 , followed by
O-O. You also meet moves like 5.Be3 , 5.Bf4 or 5.Bc4 , which lead to positions
that we cover via @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pp1p/3p1np1/8/3PP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/
R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@ 4.Be3 , 4.Bf4 or 4.Bc4 , to use these concrete
moves as examples.} Bg7 5. Be2 {As mentioned in the overview on move four,
White has a wide choice here. The move 5.Be2 is called the 'Classical
Variation'. There are many 'Classical Variations' in various openings, and the
Pirc has one, too. What is the definition of 'Classical' in Chess? The
Classical values go back to the beginning of Chess as a subject of systematic
research. Concepts like 'controlling the centre with pawns', 'developing
pieces quickly', 'play for quick castling', 'keep a sound pawn structure' were
developed by the greats of the past; names like Steinitz or Tarrasch come to
mind. A 'Classical Variation' follows these guidelines - sensible and logical,
without being too fancy. In the Classical Pirc, White plays 5.Be2 and 6.O-O,
when Black has various options.} O-O 6. O-O {Very natural and indeed
'Classical'. If you look at the starting position of the Pirc, the sequence
@@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pp1p/3p1np1/8/3PP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0
4@@EndFEN@@ 4.Nf3 Bg7 5.Be2 O-O is the fastest way to accomplish Kingside
castling.} a6 {Well, that's not a very Classical reply, is it? No, it's not...
but that idea went out the window on move one! Jokes aside, what does 6...a6
accomplish? It's a rather sophisticated idea and best understood if you think
about pawn formations and the future places for the Queenside pieces. One
fundamental choice is the positioning of the Knight -do we go to c6 or d7? One
popular way to play for Black is the formation ...c6, ...Nbd7, and ...e5 later.
This approach, starting with 6...c6 , is Black's most popular line and has a
sound reputation. One drawback of this line is the relatively passive position
of the d7-Knight, obstructing the c8-Bishop. If you develop this Bishop to g4
first, you'll often have to surrender the Bishop pair after h3. Not the end of
the world, but the line 6...Bg4 didn't look too attractive to us for this
reason. It is not very flexible. The following line we checked was 6...Nc6 ,
developing the Knight to its most active square and preparing ...e5. Black is
doing alright in this line, but we disliked that after 7.d5 Black's best is 7..
.Nb8 . This is a playable option but still not particularly attractive.
Finally, we'll get to the move that we recommend, 6...a6 . The small pawn move
has more than one purpose. The one you notice first: playing ...b5, opening b7
for the Bishop, and getting ...b5-b4 on the map. However, we will only play
the move ...b5 in some cases, and never on move seven! We'll discuss this in a
moment, but we need to talk about the less obvious idea behind 6...a6 . A
drawback of 6...Nc6 is the line 7.d5 Nb8 . If we play @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/
ppp1ppbp/3p1np1/8/3PP3/2N2N2/PPP1BPPP/R1BQ1RK1 b - - 5 6@@EndFEN@@ 6...a6 , we
can retreat to a7 instead. This unconventional idea works well. For example,
after 7.Re1 Nc6 8.d5 Na7! was successfully played by Magnus Carlsen and Levon
Aronian. An additional point: In many cases, White will interpret 6...a6 as
only geared towards ...b5 and automatically replies 7.a4 when after 7...Nc6 8.
d5 we have the opportunity to play 8...Nb4! So what about ...b5? Do we ever
play it? Yes, there are some cases, but we prioritize ...Nc6 and play ...e5
next, if possible. If White stops this idea, ...b5 becomes more relevant. In
the present chapter, we will look at lines like @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/1pp1ppbp/
p2p1np1/8/3PP3/2N2N2/PPP1BPPP/R1BQ1RK1 w - - 0 7@@EndFEN@@ 7.Bf4 Nc6 8.h3 when
we play 8...b5 . This advance needs to be well-timed; Earlier ...b5 pushes
don't work well due to e4-e5 ideas. Lines like @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/1pp1ppbp/
p2p1np1/8/3PP3/2N2N2/PPP1BPPP/R1BQ1RK1 w - - 0 7@@EndFEN@@ 7.Re1 b5?! 8.e5 are
