- - 5 6@@EndFEN@@ 6...Nc6 7.d5 and @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/ppp1ppbp/3p1np1/8/3PP3/
2N2N2/PPP1BPPP/R1BQ1RK1 b - - 5 6@@EndFEN@@ 6...a6 7.a4 Nc6 8.d5 . The pawn
move a2-a4. White weakened the square b4, so we are happy to use this more
active square. Next, we'd like to put pressure on White's d-pawn by playing ...
e6 or ...c6. An important point to keep in mind: whenever White moves his Nc3,
we need to take care that our Nb4 does not get trapped by c2-c3. At the moment
We don't have a square to jump to safely. It is not easy for White to set this
idea into motion, but we need to be aware of it. It's rather embarrassing to
get your Knight trapped 😀. In some cases we need to consider a6-a5 to
create a retreat square, which also explains why 9.a5 is considered to be the
critical test of Black's concept.} 9. a5 {Now we don't have the option to play
...a5 anymore. We continue with the standard pawn break already mentioned.} e6
{This is the correct plan in the position. We can't play 9...c6? because 10.
Ra4! would be very strong. After the much better 9...e6! White's Ra4 idea is
de-fanged.} 10. Ra4 {White attacks our brave Nb4. But we are well-prepared for
