d5 Ne7 9.b4 Ne8 10.c5 which shows this idea put into motion very quickly. In
our Pirc line, the pawn is on c2, making a similar scenario much more
difficult to achieve for White. The Knight on c3 needs to move first, which
costs some time. Black's game is rather easy, in comparison. We'll play ...Ne8
and ...f5, starting our play on the Kingside, basically no matter what White
does on the next moves. We'll have a look at some possible moves to discuss
more ideas.} 10. Be3 {White develops the Bishop to a natural square. In some
