which leads to the same position.} Ne8 {According to plan. We need to prepare .
..f5 as soon as possible.} 11. Nd2 {White intends to answer ...f5 with f3.} f5
12. f3 {White protects his e4-pawn and secures a retreat for the Bishop. We
were threatening ...f4, trapping it.} Nf6 {Here 12...f4 is possible, but more
or less an 'All-In!'-move, to use a poker term. After 13.Bf2 g5 White needs to
find the right plan 14.a5! followed by Na4 and c4-c5, when it's a matter of
who crashes through first. Computers love White, but it is not clear at all in
a game between human players. Engines tend to overestimate the static features,
so don't be too scared to enter such a position. In this particular situation,
we still recommend the move 12...Nf6 ., The plan ...Nh5-f4 looks strong and
less committal. You can also consider 12...Kh8 , intending ...Ng8 and ...Bh6,
for a more strategic approach.} 13. a5 Nh5 {The Knight is on the way to f4,
and you can still play ...g6-g5 and ...Ng6 later to drum up an attack. A great
position to fight for the win and get an exciting game.} *

