.Be6 are annoying and should be stopped. Finally, the square e7 is a good spot
for the Queen, connecting the Rooks and allowing a Rook to d8. To summarize:
our target setup is ...Be6, ...h6, ...Qe7, then probably a Rook to d8. Of
course, White is moving in the meantime, and we need to adjust. Still, keep
this setup in mind. White has several possible continuations now, and all the
permutations of Be3/Bg5/Bc4 can be irritating at first. However, all the
variations follow the same storyline: we try to achieve the target setup,
while White tries to prevent it and gain control of d5. Before we look at some
moves, we'd like to mention that Black scores very well in the dxe5 positions,
even though White should not be worse. One reason might be that White is often
not prepared for the ...a6 & ...Nc6 lines and seeks a simple solution. If you
have never studied it, closing the centre with d4-d5 is not an easy decision.
It leads to positions that are much more in the spirit of the Classical King's
Indian, quite a long way from what a 1.e4-player usually gets on the board. We
have seen that keeping the tension is unchallengeable, which leaves the dxe5
option. So frequently, White plays it as a 'cop out' with a somewhat weak
mindset. We think this is the main reason for White's bad score, not the
actual positions' quality. There are players on the White side that play these
positions to press small advantages and grind us down. But don't think that
White is after simplifications and a draw after the exchange; looks can be
deceiving. However, there will be players @@StartBracket@@see White's lousy
score@@EndBracket@@ who view the trade on e5 as a way to avoid complications
and simplify the game as much as possible. Against these players, it is
crucial not to accept a draw readily but to continue playing and accumulating
small advantages. A good strategy can be to offer trades that are favourable
for us. If White is too keen on exchanging all pieces, these offers can be
tempting. Even sterile positions often can be won by pure persistence - play
on until they break down.} dxe5 10. Bc4 {White also frequently plays 10.Bg5 or
