being. We plan to develop our Kingside by fianchettoing the dark-squared
Bishop with ...g6 and ...Bg7. The Knight usually jumps to f6, and we are ready
to castle Kingside quickly.} 2. d4 {White occupies the centre with the perfect
pawn duo on e4 and d4, a very natural move. White occasionally plays without
d4, for example by playing 2.Nc3 or 2.Bc4 . Black's Pirc setup with ...g6, ...
Bg7 and ...O-O is a good answer to these offbeat lines, too.} Nf6 {The Knight
immediately attacks the e4-pawn. This reduces White's options, compared to
playing 2...g6 or the similar @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/
RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@ 1.e4 g6 2.d4 Bg7 , which allows White to play
3.c4 amongst others. After 2...Nf6 , White's overwhelming main move is 3.Nc3
on which we will focus in the Short & Sweet.} 3. Nc3 g6 {After 3...g6 we have
reached the starting position of the Pirc Defense.} 4. Be3 {White develops the
Bishop to a natural square while still keeping many options open. The main
virtue of 4.Be3 is its flexibility, which poses a challenge to Black. White
might intend to continue with Qd2, Bh6 and h2-h4-h5 to play for a first-round
knockout, but there are other interpretations of the move, involving Nf3 and
O-O. We need to check these various ideas by White to match White's flexible
way of thinking. However, before entertaining any sophisticated thoughts, we
need to address the simple question: what is our reply to 4.Be3?} a6 {The move
4...a6! is not the only playable move against 4.Be3, but we still award it an
exclamation mark. It is essential to realize that the natural move 4...Bg7?!
does not fit the bill. This move looks like an automatic choice. We indeed
continue like that in most cases, for example, after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/
ppp1pp1p/3p1np1/8/3PP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@ 4.f4 or 4.
Nf3 . However, against 4.Be3 , there is a concrete problem: White has the
aggressive attacking plan of 5.Qd2, followed by Bh6. This straightforward
approach is very effective. After Bh6, Black either needs to take the Bishop,
losing more time @@StartBracket@@...Bf8-g7-h6@@EndBracket@@, or castle into
the murderous h4-h5 attack. It sounds harsh, but 4...Bg7?! 5.Qd2 is not only
better for White but would also be very simple to play for our opponent. We
need to be more cunning and therefore suggest a different approach. If 4...
Bg7?! is out of contention, the moves 4...c6 and 4...a6 are the main ideas for
Black. Now, this is the moment to consider that White has the option of the
caveman attack but might switch to a slower approach and continue with Nf3 and
castle Kingside. This means we need to select a move that also fits into these
scenarios. If you intend to play 4...c6 , you also need to play with ...c6
against the Classical system with 4.Nf3. This approach is chosen by Pirc
expert Mihail Marin in his GM Repertoire book, for example. We think that
playing with 4...a6! is an exciting and less explored option for Black. It
turns out that the transpositions into the Classical are no problem, as ...a6
is a viable and interesting reply to these lines, as well. Now, how does it
continue from here? We want to organize a quick counterplay on the Queenside
and delay developing our Kingside Bishop. With 4...a6 , we like to wait and
see what White's plan is. Here's an overview of White's ideas: A. Go for the
Kingside attack and usually castle Queenside. The starting moves for this idea
are 5.Qd2 and 5.f3 . B. White does not intend to throw the kitchen sink with
f3 & g4 but develops with 5.Nf3 . This still could involve aggressive ideas
with Qd2 and Bh6, but it might also just prepare O-O and lead to calmer play.}
5. Qd2 {The setup with Qd2 and f3 is a popular choice for White. The basic
idea is to aim for Queenside castling and attack on the kingside or in the
centre. The pawn move f3 covers the e-pawn and prepares g4, a move that you'll
face frequently. One reason for the popularity of White's system is the
similarity to some Sicilian variations that White might know or have in their
repertoire. Famous examples are the 'English Attack' against the Najdorf
@@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@
1.e4 c5 2.Nf3 d6 3.d4 cxd4 4.Nxd4 Nf6 5.Nc3 a6 6.Be3 e6 7.f3 Be7 8.Qd2 or the
Rauzer setup against the Dragon @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/
RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@ 1.e4 c5 2.Nf3 d6 3.d4 cxd4 4.Nxd4 Nf6 5.Nc3 g6
6.Be3 Bg7 7.f3 O-O 8.Qd2 . White's idea is simple and often very effective:
develop the pieces on the Queenside first @@StartBracket@@ Be3 and Qd2
@@EndBracket@@, support the central pawn e4 by playing f3, castle Queenside,
and push the Kingside pawns forward. An additional idea we need to be aware of
is Bh6 for White. We usually don't want to play ...Bg7 early on and allow Bh6
with a tempo. We avoided @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pp1p/3p1np1/8/3PP3/2N1B3/
PPP2PPP/R2QKBNR b KQkq - 1 4@@EndFEN@@ 4...Bg7 , and played 4...a6 for this
exact reason. Let's continue with some moves and discuss strategies in more
depth on move six, after the main continuation @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/1pp1pp1p/
p2p1np1/8/3PP3/2N1B3/PPPQ1PPP/R3KBNR b KQkq - 1 5@@EndFEN@@ 5...b5 6.f3 Nbd7}
b5 {'Hello World!', our b-pawn shouts. We don't hesitate to start our
Queenside counterplay, anticipating that White intends to castle to this side
of the board. Now White needs to react to our threat of pushing our b-pawn to
b4.} 6. f3 {The main move by a mile. White supports the centre with the f-pawn
and prepares a later g4 attack at the same time. Quite frequently, this
position arises via other move orders, like @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/1pp1pp1p/
p2p1np1/8/3PP3/2N1B3/PPP2PPP/R2QKBNR w KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@ 5.f3 b5 6.Qd2 or
@@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pp1p/3p1np1/8/3PP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0
4@@EndFEN@@ 4.f3 a6 5.Be3 b5 6.Qd2} Nbd7 {This is the most flexible move and
better than the Bishop moves. Well, if we'd play ...Bg7, White's answer Bh6,
is annoying. If we'd take White's Bishop, we lose a tempo compared to lines
where we kept the Bishop on f8. We'd capture in two moves
@@StartBracket@@Bf8-g7xh6@@EndBracket@@ instead of one
@@StartBracket@@Bf8xh6@@EndBracket@@. What about our other Bishop, the
light-squared one? On b7, the light-squared Bishop would bang its head against
a wall of White pawns: g2, f3 and e4. By playing ...Nbd7 first, we prepare to
attack White's centre with either ...e5 or ...c5. An additional idea is the
Knight transfer to b6. From b6, it has access to c4. The move 6...Nbd7 also
anticipates White's g4-g5 push. We'd like to have the option to play ...Nf6-d7
in response to g5. White now usually continues 7.O-O-O or 7.g4 if he has
Kingside play in mind, but 7.a4 is also met quite frequently. After
@@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/2pnpp1p/p2p1np1/1p6/3PP3/2N1BP2/PPPQ2PP/R3KBNR w KQkq - 1
7@@EndFEN@@ 7.a4 b4 9.Nd1 c5 Black gets good play on the Queenside and equal
chances.} 7. O-O-O {If White does not play 7.g4 , this is most likely the way
he will continue the game.} Nb6 {We already discussed earlier that we rather
want to avoid Bishop moves for the moment. The move ...Nb6 is useful to
connect it to the c4-square and frees the d7-square for his fellow on f6.
White has tried many moves here and we'll analyze some of them to get a better
picture. The most likely moves to face are 8.h4 our mainline, and 8.g4 . These
moves lead to quite different positions, so there is no 'general strategy' at
this point.} 8. h4 {If you play the Pirc regularly, you will be getting used
to this move. It's played often, in various lines, and is not very subtle. In
most cases, we should stop the pawn immediately.} h5 {'You shall not pass!'
After ...h5 it's not easy for White to open files on the kingside without
sacrificing a pawn. They would need to play g4 at some point, but we control
the square g4 with h5, Nf6, and Bc8. Playing for g4 is not White's only plan,
though. Let's discuss some general points about both side's ideas. The
position is closed at the moment, in the sense that all pawns are still on the
board. It is not a 'closed centre', though, when all the action is happening
on the wings sometimes. Let's take an example: @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/
8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@ 1.d4 Nf6 2.c4 c5 5.d5 e5 4.Nc3
d6 5.e4 - In this Benoni structure the centre is closed and can't be easily
opened. There won't be any open d-file any time soon. In our position in the
Pirc, the position is closed in the sense that there is no contact yet between
the two armies, but hostilities might happen at any time. White could prepare
g4, but also pawn pushes like f3-f4-f5 or e4-e5. On the other hand, Black
might attack White's centre with ...e5, ...c5 or push forward on the Queenside.
You notice all the ideas are based on pawn breaks and structure changes. For
Black, the key to these positions is to place the pieces well and prepare for
the opponent's advances. At the same time, you need to make sure to make
progress with your own play. Our play needs to be prophylactic in the best
possible sense: watch out for your opponent's ideas, but do so with
constructive moves that are not purely defensive. So, how should Black's setup
look like to meet these requirements? Black has a set of useful moves that fit
well and form a harmonious setup. You mostly need to consider the order of the
moves. Here's a guideline: - If White plays Nh3, take it with our Bishop. Our
Bishop has a hard time finding a proper role, and White's Knight can improve
to g5. This is more important than the Bishop-pair at the moment. White will
often play 9.Nh3 right away or in the near future. We think this move/idea is
White's best shot. - The pawn move ...c6 is essential. We cover the square d5,
which is very important to be equipped for e4-e5 by White. After e4-e5, we
gain the d5-square for the Knights, and we need the maximum stability on this
square. - After ...c6, we can play ...Qc7, which is a versatile addition to
our setup. The Queen supports ...e5 or ...c5 and makes e4-e5 more challenging
to play. - After the moves h4 and ...h5 are on the board, White's Bh6-idea is
impossible, and ...Bg7 becomes an option. - The move ...e6 can help strengthen
the control of d5 @@StartBracket@@...c6 was a first step@@EndBracket@@ and
make White's e4-e5-e6 push impossible. - Finally, there is ...Rb8, which can
be prepare ...Nc4 or ...Na4, when the b-file might open later. This list of
moves is ordered roughly by 'urgency', so you'd usually start with ...c6, ...
Qc7, ...Bg7, only then consider ...Rb8 or more direct action. We need those
moves first to get stability, then see what to do next. What you don't want to
do: castle too soon! It is only a good idea once you have a clearer picture of
the pawn structure and central action. You might want to castle if the centre
opens up and you need to involve the h8-Rook quickly. If the centre is open,
an attack based on g4 is also less likely to work, making the King safer on
the Kingside. So castling has to be carefully considered; it is never a
'routine move', but needs to be a conscious decision, based on the specific
situation. White is playing moves, too... and this requires adjustments, of
course. We'll examine some lines now and discuss White's ideas in the process.}
9. Nh3 {We think this is the most likely move to happen and the most
challenging at the same time. If you consider the position before
@@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/2p1pp1p/pn1p1np1/1p6/3PP3/2N1BP2/PPPQ2PP/2KR1BNR w kq - 3
8@@EndFEN@@ 8.h4 White had problems developing the Kingside Knight. Playing
Nge2 doesn't work due to ...Nc4, so what to do? The move 8.h4 not only showed
attacking ambitions but also prepared the Knight development to h3. From h3,
the Knight might jump to g5 or go to f2. This is not too important, as we'll
take the Knight anyway, as discussed before. White may also delay Nh3 and
start with a different move, but go for Nh3 later. The sequence 9.Bd3 c6 10.
Nh3 Bxh3 11.Rxh3 is possible and transposes to @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/2p1pp1p/
pn1p1np1/1p6/3PP3/2N1BP2/PPPQ2PP/2KR1BNR w kq - 3 8@@EndFEN@@ 8.h4 h5 9.Nh3
Bxh3 10.Rxh3 c6 11.Bd3 which we will analyze in a moment.} Bxh3 {According to
plan.} 10. Rxh3 c6 {We suggest starting with this move, followed by ...Qc7 and
...Bg7 next. Now White's pawn push e4-e5 does not trouble us. We think that 11.
Bd3 strengthens the e4-e5 push idea and is the most challenging move.} 11. Bd3
{White prepares e5-e6, which looks like White's best plan.} Qc7 {A good place
for the Queen. In some of the following lines we'll see that it is slightly
more precise to move the Queen first and delay ...Bg7.} 12. Kb1 {A good
prophylactic move, preparing e4-e5. The immediate 12.e5 dxe5 13.dxe5 Nfd5 14.
Nxd5 Nxd5 is premature, but now a more serious idea.} Bg7 {The next step to
complete our setup. Now we are ready to answer 13.e5 with 13...dxe5 14.dxe5
Nfd5 and gain the excellent d5-outpost. The position is complex and offers
plenty of play for both sides.} *

