moves lead to quite different positions, so there is no 'general strategy' at
this point.} 8. g4 {The move g4 is very popular for White in this type of
position. White gains space and prepares h4-h5 or g4-g5. After the best reply,
Black gets a good game without any trouble.} h5 {This is a strong defensive
move. We immediately force White to decide about the fate of the g-pawn. In
both cases, 9.gxh5 or 9.g5 White has a hard time opening the Kingside position.
With h5! we at least slow down White's play considerably.} 9. g5 {White grabs
space on the Kingside but closes this part of the board. Any attack will
likely involve the push of the f-pawn now.} Nfd7 10. f4 {Using the f-pawn is
the only way forward for White.} b4 {The b-pawn advance not only gains space
on 'our' side of the board but also pushes away the defender of the e4-pawn.
After White played f4, the e4-pawn becomes a target. We'll check both Knight
moves now, mostly because 11.Nce2 requires a non-standard reply.} 11. Nb1 {
White needs to react to our threat to take the c3-Knight and retreats. We also
looked at the alternative 11.Nce2} Bb7 {We develop a piece in combination with
a threat. That's often welcome.} 12. d5 {White needs to play this to limit the
damage. After 12.Bd3?! c5 the Bishop turns out to be misplaced.} c5 {We don't
want to allow White to put his Bishop on d4. Now Black is in good shape, as 13.
dxc6 Bxc6 14.Qxb4 gives Black good play after 14...Rb8 , 14...Bg7 or 14...Na4 .
