attack.} b4 {This is best. Note that 10...O-O? 11.Ng3 is good for White.
Compared to @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/2p1ppbp/pn1p2p1/1p4Pn/3PP3/1PN1BP2/P1PQ3P/
R3KBNR w KQkq - 1 10@@EndFEN@@ 10.O-O-O O-O! we lack the play against the
White King on the weakened Queenside.} 11. Nd1 c5 {A logical move, but 11...a5
also works well.} 12. Ng3 {According to plan: White wants to get rid of our
Knight and open the h-file.} O-O {We avoid ...Nxg3 and accept a weakening of
our pawn structure, but this structural deficit is tough to exploit for White.
White's King won't find a safe place for the rest of the game.} 13. Nxh5 gxh5 {
We have reached an unexplored and 'clearly unclear' position 😀 Stockfish
thinks it's an equal position, but obviously, a draw is unlikely from such a
sharp situation. Playing training games from this position with a training
partner would certainly be a rewarding experience. We conclude with some
possible ideas from here: A @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/4ppbp/pn1p4/2p3Pp/1p1PP3/
