1. e4 d6 {This is the starting move of the Pirc Defense. We open the c8-h3
diagonal for our light-squared Bishop, but this is not the primary purpose of
that move. By playing 1...d6 we stop White from pushing e4-e5 for the time
being. We plan to develop our Kingside by fianchettoing the dark-squared
Bishop with ...g6 and ...Bg7. The Knight usually jumps to f6, and we are ready
to castle Kingside quickly.} 2. d4 {White occupies the centre with the perfect
pawn duo on e4 and d4, a very natural move. White occasionally plays without
d4, for example by playing 2.Nc3 or 2.Bc4 . Black's Pirc setup with ...g6, ...
Bg7 and ...O-O is a good answer to these offbeat lines, too.} Nf6 {The Knight
immediately attacks the e4-pawn. This reduces White's options, compared to
playing 2...g6 or the similar @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/
RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@ 1.e4 g6 2.d4 Bg7 , which allows White to play
3.c4 amongst others. After 2...Nf6 , White's overwhelming main move is 3.Nc3
on which we will focus in the Short & Sweet.} 3. Nc3 g6 {After 3...g6 we have
reached the starting position of the Pirc Defense.} 4. Be3 {White develops the
Bishop to a natural square while still keeping many options open. The main
virtue of 4.Be3 is its flexibility, which poses a challenge to Black. White
might intend to continue with Qd2, Bh6 and h2-h4-h5 to play for a first-round
knockout, but there are other interpretations of the move, involving Nf3 and
O-O. We need to check these various ideas by White to match White's flexible
way of thinking. However, before entertaining any sophisticated thoughts, we
need to address the simple question: what is our reply to 4.Be3?} a6 {The move
4...a6! is not the only playable move against 4.Be3, but we still award it an
exclamation mark. It is essential to realize that the natural move 4...Bg7?!
does not fit the bill. This move looks like an automatic choice. We indeed
continue like that in most cases, for example, after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/
ppp1pp1p/3p1np1/8/3PP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@ 4.f4 or 4.
Nf3 . However, against 4.Be3 , there is a concrete problem: White has the
aggressive attacking plan of 5.Qd2, followed by Bh6. This straightforward
approach is very effective. After Bh6, Black either needs to take the Bishop,
losing more time @@StartBracket@@...Bf8-g7-h6@@EndBracket@@, or castle into
the murderous h4-h5 attack. It sounds harsh, but 4...Bg7?! 5.Qd2 is not only
better for White but would also be very simple to play for our opponent. We
need to be more cunning and therefore suggest a different approach. If 4...
Bg7?! is out of contention, the moves 4...c6 and 4...a6 are the main ideas for
Black. Now, this is the moment to consider that White has the option of the
caveman attack but might switch to a slower approach and continue with Nf3 and
castle Kingside. This means we need to select a move that also fits into these
scenarios. If you intend to play 4...c6 , you also need to play with ...c6
against the Classical system with 4.Nf3. This approach is chosen by Pirc
expert Mihail Marin in his GM Repertoire book, for example. We think that
playing with 4...a6! is an exciting and less explored option for Black. It
turns out that the transpositions into the Classical are no problem, as ...a6
is a viable and interesting reply to these lines, as well. Now, how does it
continue from here? We want to organize a quick counterplay on the Queenside
and delay developing our Kingside Bishop. With 4...a6 , we like to wait and
see what White's plan is. Here's an overview of White's ideas: A. Go for the
Kingside attack and usually castle Queenside. The starting moves for this idea
are 5.Qd2 and 5.f3 . B. White does not intend to throw the kitchen sink with
f3 & g4 but develops with 5.Nf3 . This still could involve aggressive ideas
with Qd2 and Bh6, but it might also just prepare O-O and lead to calmer play.}
5. Nf3 {A natural move, developing the Kingside first. White remains flexible
and does not yet commit to a certain strategy. Castling Queenside or Kingside
are still possible, for example.} Bg7 {After 5...Bg7 White has the choice
between two main strategies. The first one is to continue with 6.Qd2 , go for
Queenside castling and attack with moves like Bh6 and h4. It's no surprise
that these lines are very sharp and exciting to study. White's alternative is
a more strategic approach, involving moves like a4 and h3, similar to many
positions in the Classical Variation. In the Classical, a sequence like
@@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pp1p/3p1np1/8/3PP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0
4@@EndFEN@@ 4.Nf3 Bg7 5.Be2 O-O 6.O-O a6 7.h3 Nc6 8.a4 is played with the same
mindset: control the centre and restrain counterplay. We examine White's
slower setup using the move order @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/1pp1ppbp/p2p1np1/8/3PP3/
2N1BN2/PPP2PPP/R2QKB1R w KQkq - 2 6@@EndFEN@@ 6.h3 , but 6.a4 O-O 7.h3 is also
standard.} 6. Qd2 {White is after a quick Queenside castling and possibly Bh6
to trade our Bishop. The following lines are very sharp and exciting, so
fasten your seatbelt. Instead of 6.Qd2 , White also has the more strategic
approach 6.h3 O-O 7.a4 , when we play our usual setup with 7...Nc6 , which is
similar to the Classical Variation and might even transpose into this line. If
you know the general ideas of the Classical, you are going to be fine for the
moment. For the purpose of the Short & Sweet, we focus on the sharper attempts
starting with 6.Qd2} O-O {We also checked the move 6...b5 here. It is a good
alternative, but we think 6...O-O is a better choice.} 7. Bh6 {White goes for
the Bishop exchange, a typical attacking device. Our Bishop is a crucial
defender of the King, so trading it makes a lot of sense. An additional idea
for White is not to take on g7 but to keep the Bishop on h6 and play h4-h5.
The Bishop on h6 stops Black's ...h5-reply against h4, which is a commonly
seen idea in our repertoire. Sounds great for White, but there is a downside.
This type of play is time-consuming, and our counterplay arrives in time.
Instead of 7.Bh6 , White also has tried 7.O-O-O , when 7...b5 8.Bd3 c5! is a
new idea that leads to sharp play and good chances for Black.} b5 {We finally
launch our counterplay with the b-pawn.} 8. Bxg7 {White exchanges the
dark-squared Bishops right away. This makes out King position somewhat safer,
as a one attacking option can be h4-h5, which is more dangerous if White keeps
the tension with the Bishops still being on the board. After the trade on g7
White's h-pawn push could be stopped by ...h5.} Kxg7 9. Bd3 {White needs to
take care of the e4-pawn given our ...b4-idea. 9.Bd3 is a natural way to
defend the important pawn. Instead 9.e5 dxe5 10.dxe5 Qxd2+ leads nowhere, as
the advanced e-pawn is more of a liability for White than an asset.} Nc6 {We
develop our Queenside Knight and take more control of the dark squares in the
centre of the board. It is somewhat uncommon to place the Knight in front of
the c-pawn, but it works well here. In addition, a setup with ...Bb7 and ...
Nbd7 is not possible here, as both 9...Nbd7? and 9...Bb7? are refuted by 10.e5
. We are just too slow to complete this setup. After our choice 9...Nc6 , the
only critical test is 10.e5 . A slow move can't trouble Black; we'd have time
to play ...e5 with a good game.} 10. e5 {This is the acid test of our concept.
If we'd manage to play ...e5, there is no reason at all why White would have
any claim to an advantage. You could even argue that White's pieces are
slightly misplaced, as the Bishop on d3. The move 10.e5 is critical, as it
seeks to activate White's pieces with tempo. The play is very concrete and
tactical now.} dxe5 {We need to take on e5 first, so after 10...dxe5 11.dxe5
Ng4 , the pawn is hanging. After 10...Ng4? 11.Be4 we have no good move.} 11.
dxe5 Ng4 {White's pawn on e5 is under fire. They need to play precisely now to
pose any problems.} 12. O-O-O {White's best try and the most popular move.
After we have traded on e5, the move 12.Be4? is just awful for White after 12..
.Qxd2+ 13.Kxd2 Bb7 shows. White's King is stuck in the centre, and e5 is weak.
White also has 12.Qf4?! , which falls into the trap 12...Ncxe5! 13.Nxe5 Qd6!
which is already a bit better for Black.} Ngxe5 {We suggest taking this
hanging pawn. As the saying goes: 'The proof of the pudding is in the eating',
right? Well, this move is a novelty, as all games so far featured 12...b4 . We
examined this move closely, but prefer our choice. Now, what happens after the
capture on e5? The next few moves are more or less forced when we reach an
important parting of the ways on move 17.} 13. Nxe5 {The most natural and only
dangerous move.} Nxe5 14. Qe2 {Again, the most testing, forcing us to take on
d3. Instead 14.Qe3 Ng4 or @@StartFEN@@r1bq1r2/2p1ppkp/p5p1/1p2n3/8/2NB4/
PPPQ1PPP/2KR3R w - - 0 14@@EndFEN@@ 14.Qf4 Qd6 are harmless.} Nxd3+ 15. Rxd3
Qe8 16. Nd5 {We have eaten the pudding, but White has some activity for it.
The Knight jump to d5 is best for White here. Instead, 16.Qe5+?! f6 17.Qxc7
Bf5 is easy to handle.} Bf5 {We get the Bishop out with tempo. After
@@StartFEN@@r1b1qr2/2p1ppkp/p5p1/1p6/8/2NR4/PPP1QPPP/2K4R w - - 1 16@@EndFEN@@
16.Nd5 it's clear that White has enough play to get the pawn back - they can
try various lines now to regain the pawn. We think it makes little sense to
learn all these lines by heart up to move 25 or so. Here are the main tries
that we have analyzed. A. @@StartFEN@@r3qr2/2p1ppkp/p5p1/1p1N1b2/8/3R4/
PPP1QPPP/2K4R w - - 3 17@@EndFEN@@ 17.Rd2 Qc6 18.Re1! Pointed out by the comp
as being the only challenging move. More natural moves like the captures lead
nowhere. 18...Rad8 19.Qe5+ Kh6 This looks scary at first, but we have a nice
defensive resource 20.Nxe7 Rxd2! 21.Qf4+ Kg7 22.Nxc6 Rxc2+ 23.Kd1 Rxc6 We have
enough material for the Queen and good anchor squares for the pieces, like e6.
White may try to play for the win, but this can easily backfire. We might get
a dangerous passed pawn on the Queenside, for example. B. @@StartFEN@@r3qr2/
2p1ppkp/p5p1/1p1N1b2/8/3R4/PPP1QPPP/2K4R w - - 3 17@@EndFEN@@ 17.Rc3 Rd8 18.
Nxe7 Instead 18.Qe5+ f6 19.Qxe7+ Qxe7 20.Nxe7 Be4 21.f3 Rde8! leads nowhere
for White. @@StartFEN@@3rqr2/2p1Npkp/p5p1/1p3b2/8/2R5/PPP1QPPP/2K4R b - - 0
18@@EndFEN@@ 18...Bg4! 19.f3 Rd6 20.fxg4 Re6 , and we get the piece back, with
equality C. @@StartFEN@@r3qr2/2p1ppkp/p5p1/1p1N1b2/8/3R4/PPP1QPPP/2K4R w - - 3
17@@EndFEN@@ 17.Re3 Qc6 18.Nxe7 Qf6 Here, we activate the Queen nicely and
have equal chances.} *

