@@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@
1.d4 Nf6 2.Bf4 g6 3.Nc3 d6 4.e4 is a standard sequence of moves, leading to
our starting point on the fourth move. The early Bishop development might
signal White's intention to castle Queenside and start an attack on the other
side of the board. Here we look at Bf4, which is less popular than the similar
alternatives @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pp1p/3p1np1/8/3PP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR
w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@ 4.Be3 and 4.Bg5 . In comparison, White takes more
control over e5, so the pawn push e4-e5 needs to be on our radar. On the other
hand, White cannot operate with the pawn move to f4 that easily anymore. This
is a substantial difference to lines like @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pp1p/3p1np1/
8/3PP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@ 4.Bg5 Bg7 5.f4 or
@@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pp1p/3p1np1/8/3PP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0
4@@EndFEN@@ 4.Be3 a6 5.h3 Bg7 6.f4 . The noteworthy tactical point is that the
Bishop on f4 might get attacked by ...Nh5 or ...e5 later on. The ...e5-push
attacks the Bishop, winning time. Therefore it becomes an option even after
d4-d5 attacks a Knight on c6 - you answer d4-d5 with ...e7-e5 with a
counterattack. Before we continue with Black's reply, we'd like to add that
White also employs the line @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pp1p/3p1np1/8/3PP3/2N5/
PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@ 4.Nf3 Bg7 5.Bf4 , which we suggest to
answer with 5...a6 . Our reply against @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pp1p/3p1np1/8/
3PP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@ 4.Bf4 is also 4...a6 , after
which 5.Nf3 Bg7 leads to the same position. Finally, there is a third way to
play Bf4 for White. White sometimes plays @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pp1p/3p1np1/
8/3PP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@ 4.Nf3 Bg7 5.h3 O-O 6.Bf4
which we also answer with an ...a6-setup. The various versions can be treated
in the same way, making it less confusing than it sounds first. This general
move order approach is identical to the one we use against the Be3 lines. We
answer @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pp1p/3p1np1/8/3PP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq
- 0 4@@EndFEN@@ 4.Be3 with 4...a6 , @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pp1p/3p1np1/8/
3PP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@ 4.Nf3 Bg7 5.Be3 with 5...a6 ,
and @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pp1p/3p1np1/8/3PP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq -
0 4@@EndFEN@@ 4.Nf3 Bg7 5.h3 O-O 6.Be3 with 6...a6 . We'll discuss the merits
of the early ...a6! now.} a6 {Similar to the @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pp1p/
3p1np1/8/3PP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@ 4.Be3 a6! line, we
immediately start counterplay on the Queenside. We need to be aware of White's
idea to play a quick Qd2 and Bh6, which is extremely dangerous. The prime
example is the line @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pp1p/3p1np1/8/3PPB2/2N5/PPP2PPP/
R2QKBNR b KQkq - 1 4@@EndFEN@@ 4...Bg7 5.Qd2 O-O 6.Bh6 , which is a recipe for
disaster for Black. Our idea with @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pp1p/3p1np1/8/3PPB2/
2N5/PPP2PPP/R2QKBNR b KQkq - 1 4@@EndFEN@@ 4...a6! is to speed up the
Queenside play. If White plays Bh6, we can capture on h6 without having played
...Bg7 before, saving a tempo. The move Bh6 also wouldn't attack a Bishop on
g7, which allows us to ignore Bh6 and let White take on f8. Now, after
@@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pp1p/3p1np1/8/3PPB2/2N5/PPP2PPP/R2QKBNR b KQkq - 1
4@@EndFEN@@ 4...a6 , we mostly need to consider 5.Qd2 and 5.Nf3 . The move 5.
Nf3 we will answer with 5...Bg7 , which leads to a position that you will also
get on the board via the move order @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pp1p/3p1np1/8/
3PP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@ 4.Nf3 Bg7 5.Bf4 a6! To sum
things up: we handle the moves sequences @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pp1p/3p1np1/
8/3PP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@ 4.Be3 a6! ,
@@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pp1p/3p1np1/8/3PP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0
4@@EndFEN@@ 4.Nf3 Bg7 5.Be3 a6! , @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pp1p/3p1np1/8/3PP3/
2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@ 4.Bf4 a6! and @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/
ppp1pp1p/3p1np1/8/3PP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@ 4.Nf3 Bg7 5.
Bf4 a6! in a very consistent fashion. The Bishop moves to e3 and f4 signal
White's possible plan to go Qd2 and Bh6, which means we should start our
Queenside play immediately.} 5. Nf3 {A solid move, developing the Knight to
the most natural square. White can combine Bf4 and Nf3 in various ways. They
can also start with @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pp1p/3p1np1/8/3PP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/
R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@ 4.Nf3 , and after 4...Bg7 5.Bf4 we can answer
this move order with 5...a6 , directly transposing to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/
ppp1pp1p/3p1np1/8/3PP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@ 4.Bf4 a6 5.
Nf3 Bg7 @@StartBracket@@we'll examine this in a minute@@EndBracket@@. It's no
mistake to play @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/ppp1ppbp/3p1np1/8/3PPB2/2N2N2/PPP2PPP/
R2QKB1R b KQkq - 3 5@@EndFEN@@ 5...O-O in this particular sequence, as 6.Qd2
a6 or @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/ppp1ppbp/3p1np1/8/3PPB2/2N2N2/PPP2PPP/R2QKB1R w KQ
- 4 6@@EndFEN@@ 6.h3 a6 would transpose to lines that we cover here, too.
Instead of 5.Nf3 , you also meet 5.Qd2 , when 5...b5! shows the idea of the
early ...a6. The arising positions are similar to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/
ppp1pp1p/3p1np1/8/3PP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@ 4.Be3 a6 5.
Qd2 b5 , which we examine in the Short & Sweet, too. The Bishop on f4 is less
effective for White, compared to e3 - so nothing to complain about.} Bg7 {
After this natural move, White's main choice is between the aggressive 6.Qd2 ,
intending Bh6 and O-O-O, or a more restrained approach with moves like 6.h3
and 6.a4 .} 6. Qd2 {White prepares to castle Queenside, the most ambitious and
popular move. Instead White may also play 6.h3 O-O 7.a4 when we play 7...Nc6 .
The arising positions are very similar to the Classical and don't need to be
examined in detail in the Short & Sweet.} O-O {We think this is the most
precise move. After 6...b5 7.Bd3! White seems to better, based on a quick
e4-e5. We advise castling instead. It is useful to look at a similar line:
@@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pp1p/3p1np1/8/3PP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0
4@@EndFEN@@ 4.Be3 a6 5.Nf3 Bg7 6.Qd2 when we suggest 6...O-O , too. In both
lines, the move 7.Bh6 is the most obvious and leads to the same position. We
cover this critical line in the 4.Be3 move order, as it is the far more
popular way to reach the same position. Instead of 7.Bh6 , White's main
alternative is 7.O-O-O} 7. O-O-O b5 {Here we go! Again, we should compare to
the 4.Be3-line: After @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pp1p/3p1np1/8/3PP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/
R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@ 4.Be3 a6 5.Nf3 Bg7 6.Qd2 O-O 7.O-O-O we play 7.
..b5 , too. There are some differences in the arising lines, but we start with
the same move.} 8. Bd3 {A logical move. White develops naturally and has a
lead in development.} c5 {A new move, instead of 8...Bb7 . We immediately
throw our pawns forward and open files, leading to a tactical mess.} 9. dxc5 {
The only good move. We were threatening both ...cxd4 and ...c4.} b4 10. Nd5 {
The most active move in the position. We expect this move to be played here,
as it looks far more logical than 10.Ne2 . After 10.Ne2 we analyze 10...Ng4!
in the main course, leading to wild complications.} Nxd5 11. exd5 dxc5 {We
have reached a razor-sharp position. As said before, we are in uncharted
waters, so we need to speculate what White may play. Black is attacking the
d5-pawn, which leads to the candidates 12.Be4 and 12.Qe3 . Both moves lead to
crazy complications. We'll show some key lines, but you could explore much
more if you like. The arising lines are fun to analyze and play!} 12. Qe3 {
White attacks c5 and operates on the assumption that 12...Qxd5 is impossible
due to 14.Be4 .} Qxd5 {Well, we CAN take the pawn and sacrifice the Rook on a8!
} 13. Be4 Qxa2 {Now it seems best for White to avoid 14.Bxa8 , at least for
practical reasons.} 14. Bxa8 {We have to check the capture, of course. White
also has 14.Qb3 which we discuss in more detail in the full course.} Qxb2+ 15.
Kd2 Rd8+ 16. Ke2 Qxc2+ {A crazy position, predictably evaluated as 0.00 by
Stockfish. We have four pawns for a Rook and hunt the White King! This is fun,
but more for Black than White, we think.} *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Short & Sweet"]
[Black "The aggressive 4.Bg5 #1"]
[Result "*"]
[PlyCount "26"]

1. e4 d6 {This is the starting move of the Pirc Defense. We open the c8-h3
diagonal for our light-squared Bishop, but this is not the primary purpose of
that move. By playing 1...d6 we stop White from pushing e4-e5 for the time
being. We plan to develop our Kingside by fianchettoing the dark-squared
Bishop with ...g6 and ...Bg7. The Knight usually jumps to f6, and we are ready
to castle Kingside quickly.} 2. d4 {White occupies the centre with the perfect
pawn duo on e4 and d4, a very natural move. White occasionally plays without
d4, for example by playing 2.Nc3 or 2.Bc4 . Black's Pirc setup with ...g6, ...
Bg7 and ...O-O is a good answer to these offbeat lines, too.} Nf6 {The Knight
immediately attacks the e4-pawn. This reduces White's options, compared to
playing 2...g6 or the similar @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/
RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@ 1.e4 g6 2.d4 Bg7 , which allows White to play
3.c4 amongst others. After 2...Nf6 , White's overwhelming main move is 3.Nc3
on which we will focus in the Short & Sweet.} 3. Nc3 g6 {After 3...g6 we have
reached the starting position of the Pirc Defense.} 4. Bg5 {This is one of
White's more aggressive setups. Similar to 4.Be3 White aims for rapid
Queenside development. Quite frequently, our opponent aims for Queenside
castling and intends to launch a Kingside attack. But why does White play 4.
Bg5 instead of 4.Be3? After 4.Bg5 the Bishop is more active than on e3. It
attacks our f6-Knight and we have to reckon with e4-e5 in many cases. Sounds
great for White but there are drawbacks. First of all, the Bishop might get
kicked away with ...h6 and possibly ...g5. In some cases, White needs to give
up the Bishop-pair, as we will see. A second point, compared to Be3 setups, is
the neglect of central control on d4 and c5. On e3 the Bishop helps to control
those squares, while on g5, and often h4 later, this piece is not connected to
the centre and Queenside action. A crucial point to mention is that White's
various continuations after 4...Bg7 - 5.Qd2 , 5.f4 , 5.Nf3 and 5.e5 - require
different responses. There is no 'one size fits all' approach or a 'setup' to
go for. Each line leads to different position types and needs a specific
answer.} Bg7 {A perfectly normal move, but we need to talk about it in more
detail. On move four, White has three reasonable moves of the Queen's Bishop,
@@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pp1p/3p1np1/8/3PP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0
4@@EndFEN@@ 4.Be3 , 4.Bf4 , and 4.Bg5 . These moves share some common ideas,
but also differ considerably in some ways. In our repertoire, we handle the
moves 4.Be3 and 4.Bf4 in the same way, by playing an immediate 4...a6! to
answer 5.Qd2 with 5...b5! We keep the Bishop on f8 to take the sting out of
White's Qd2 & Bh6 idea. The line @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pp1p/3p1np1/8/3PP3/
2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@ 4.Be3 Bg7?! 5.Qd2 and next Bh6
scores particularly well for White and should be avoided. The same applies for
@@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pp1p/3p1np1/8/3PP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0
4@@EndFEN@@ 4.Bf4 a6! , as White's Bh6 idea works just as well with a Bishop
on f4. Now, let's look at @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pp1p/3p1np1/8/3PP3/2N5/
PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@ 4.Bg5 should we play 4...a6 here, too?
No, this is a mistake due to 5.e5! highlighting a critical difference between
the Bishop placements. Therefore we suggest playing @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/
ppp1pp1p/3p1np1/8/3PP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@ 4.Bg5 Bg7!
but what about 5.Qd2 then? Is this a problem due to Bh6 next, just like after
@@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pp1p/3p1np1/8/3PP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0
4@@EndFEN@@ 4.Be3 Bg7?! No, because this time we can benefit from the Bishop
position on g5 by playing @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pp1p/3p1np1/8/3PP3/2N5/
PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@ 4.Bg5 Bg7 5.Qd2 h6! which stops the
exchange idea in its tracks. In the variations @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pp1p/
3p1np1/8/3PP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@ 4.Be3 and 4.Bf4 , we
play 4...a6 , which defines our pawn structure on the Queenside early on. How
do we handle our Queenside formation against @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pp1p/
3p1np1/8/3PP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@ 4.Bg5? This decision
depends on White's fifth move and needs to be decided on a case-by-case basis.
Some lines feature relatively uncommon ideas in the Pirc, involving the move ..
.d6-d5. In the Shirt & Sweet, we will focus on the sharpest moves 5.f4 , 5.e5
and White's main choice 5.Qd2 . White rarely plays 5.Nf3 when we recommend the
quirky 5...Nc6!?} 5. f4 {White mixes Bg5 with the Austrian Attack! Let's pause
for a minute and evaluate the current position. By playing f4 White signals
the intention to play e5 soon, an idea that we always need to have on the
radar. This idea might be more potent than usual because the Bishop on g5
often allows tactical ideas based on the vis-a-vis with our Queen. The Bishop
on g5 might be an annoyance for us, but it is also a liability for White. We
might play...h6 in the right moment when Bh4 leaves the Bishop unprotected on
h4. This point sounds less relevant at first, but hang on. An additional fact:
the square e3 is weak in White's camp, which often invites ...Ng4 to hit this
square. And last but not least, the setup Bg5 & f4 weakens White's control
over d4 and c5. We might either push ...c5 or ...e5 to take advantage of the
comparably weak d4-pawn, based on concrete tactics. All these points add up to
counterplay for Black - let's check the details.} O-O {We'd like to open the
position and attack White's centre, but first, we need to get our King to
safety. Now White's choice is between 6.Nf3 which is geared towards Kingside
castling, or 6.Qd2 heading in the other direction. These moves require
completely different replies, based on concrete tactics.} 6. Qd2 {White
prepares to castle Queenside. It is clearly premature for White to play 6.e5?!
when 6...Ng4! highlights the weakness on e3. With ...f6 next Black gets good
play. A better move is 6.Nf3 but the original reply 6...d5! is strong. We use
the fact that 7.e5 Ne4! is nice for Black and @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/ppp1ppbp/
3p1np1/6B1/3PPP2/2N5/PPP3PP/R2QKBNR w KQ - 1 6@@EndFEN@@ 6.Nf3 d5 7.Bxf6 exf6
8.Nxd5 f5! leads to trouble for White.} h6 {We can't play the immediate 6...
e5?? because 7.dxe5 dxe5 8.Qxd8 Rxd8 9.fxe5 is a disaster. Inserting
@@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/ppp1ppbp/3p1np1/6B1/3PPP2/2N5/PPPQ2PP/R3KBNR b KQ - 2
6@@EndFEN@@ 6...h6 however, makes a huge difference!} 7. Bh4 {White wants to
keep the Bishop. This move was played in all games that reached the position
after @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/ppp1ppbp/3p1np1/6B1/3PPP2/2N5/PPPQ2PP/R3KBNR b KQ -
2 6@@EndFEN@@ 6...h6} e5 {Remember when we mentioned that the Bishop could be
unprotected on h4? Here's the prime example: the shot ...Nxe4! is the great
point of 7...e5!} 8. dxe5 {The most likely move to face. After 8.fxe5 Nxe4! we
use the same tactic as after 8.dxe5.} Nxe4 {Again, this strike works well.} 9.
Bxd8 {The only move. 9.Nxe4?? Qxh4+ 10.g3 Qe7 is awful for White.} Nxd2 10. Be7
{Here, White also has the forced sequence 10.Bxc7 Nxf1 11.Kxf1 dxe5 12.Bxe5
Bxe5 13.fxe5 Bf5 , which we will check in the full course via the move order
@@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/ppp1ppb1/3p1npp/8/3PPP1B/2N5/PPPQ2PP/R3KBNR b KQ - 1
7@@EndFEN@@ 7...e5 8.fxe5 Nxe4 9.Bxd8 Nxd2 10.Bxc7 Nxf1 11.Kxf1 dxe5 12.Bxe5
Bxe5 13.dxe5 We think Black is a bit easier to play, but it is objectively
equal.} Nxf1 {This is best. Saving the Rook with 10...Re8 is bad due to 11.Bb5
. It turns out that we don't need to worry about the exchange loss.} 11. Bxf8
Kxf8 12. Kxf1 dxe5 13. fxe5 Nc6 {After a series of more or less forced move we
reach an interesting position. We lost the exchange, but we have the
Bishop-pair in an open position, and White can't keep the e5-pawn. Stockfish
gives Black a minimal advantage, at least clearly showing that there is
nothing to worry about. The two Bishops are fantastic pieces, and both will be
aimed at the White Queenside, with ...Bf5 on the agenda.} *

