.d6-d5. In the Shirt & Sweet, we will focus on the sharpest moves 5.f4 , 5.e5
and White's main choice 5.Qd2 . White rarely plays 5.Nf3 when we recommend the
quirky 5...Nc6!?} 5. e5 {White plays very aggressively and attacks our Knight.
This line yields White excellent results, but this is primarily due to Black
being unprepared. That's a mistake we are not going to make. Let's have a
closer look.} Nfd7 {Black has a fundamental decision here. You can play 5...
dxe5 or retreat the Knight. We suggest 5...Nfd7 , because it leads to more
exciting and sharp play.} 6. f4 {Alright, White wants to kill us quickly and
be done with it. Jokes aside, this is the aggressive option, and it leads to
exciting play. The arising positions look similar to lines like
@@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pp1p/3p1np1/8/3PP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0
4@@EndFEN@@ 4.f4 Bg7 5.e5 Nfd7 but the Bishop placement on g5 makes a
substantial difference. In the Austrian attack, a quick ...c5 is the crucial
move, but here this is out of the picture, as 6...c5? 7.exd6 exploits the pin.
Instead of 6.f4 , White also frequently plays 6.exd6 when 6...cxd6 7.Qd2 h6 8.
Be3 Nf6 9.h3 e6 is a good setup for Black. We keep the King in the centre and
play Nc6-e7 next, controlling d5. The e7-Knight has the option to play ...Nd5
or ...Nf5, looking to trade the Bishop.} Nb6 {Black's main move is 6...O-O ,
but this gives White various attacking options. Black seems to be fine, but we
feel 6...Nb6 is a good solution for a sideline that will not encounter
frequently. With 6...Nb6 Black does not commit the King @@StartBracket@@after
6...O-O 7.h4 is possible@@EndBracket@@ amongst others and opens up the Bishop
on c8. We will play ...f6 next to attack White's centre.} 7. Nf3 {White's
choice in about 80% of the games after @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/pppnppbp/3p2p1/
4P1B1/3P4/2N5/PPP2PPP/R2QKBNR w KQkq - 1 6@@EndFEN@@ 6.f4 Nb6 . We employ the
standard plan with ...f6.} f6 {The standard move to attack White's advanced
pawn.} 8. exf6 exf6 9. Bh4 {Here 9.Qe2+? badly backfires after 9...Kf7 when
the White Queen is awfully misplaced.} O-O {Now we are ready to comfortably
play ...d5 and start play on the light squares. White has weakened this colour
complex quite seriously.} 10. Be2 {Or 10.d5 Re8+ 11.Be2 Nc4 when Black is
happy to activate the Knight. White can play @@StartFEN@@rnbqr1k1/ppp3bp/
1n1p1pp1/3P4/5P1B/2N2N2/PPP3PP/R2QKB1R w KQ - 1 11@@EndFEN@@ 11.Kf2 but 11...
Qe7 is a good reply. Black's position is compact and has no weaknesses. Note
that White's d5-push has given up the c5-square, which can be used for the
b8-Knight.} d5 {Gaining more grip on the light squares. We play ...Nc6 and ...
Bf5 next, with equal chances.} *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Short & Sweet"]
[Black "The aggressive 4.Bg5 #3"]
[Result "*"]
[PlyCount "30"]

1. e4 d6 {This is the starting move of the Pirc Defense. We open the c8-h3
diagonal for our light-squared Bishop, but this is not the primary purpose of
that move. By playing 1...d6 we stop White from pushing e4-e5 for the time
being. We plan to develop our Kingside by fianchettoing the dark-squared
Bishop with ...g6 and ...Bg7. The Knight usually jumps to f6, and we are ready
to castle Kingside quickly.} 2. d4 {White occupies the centre with the perfect
pawn duo on e4 and d4, a very natural move. White occasionally plays without
d4, for example by playing 2.Nc3 or 2.Bc4 . Black's Pirc setup with ...g6, ...
Bg7 and ...O-O is a good answer to these offbeat lines, too.} Nf6 {The Knight
immediately attacks the e4-pawn. This reduces White's options, compared to
playing 2...g6 or the similar @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/
RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@ 1.e4 g6 2.d4 Bg7 , which allows White to play
3.c4 amongst others. After 2...Nf6 , White's overwhelming main move is 3.Nc3
on which we will focus in the Short & Sweet.} 3. Nc3 g6 {After 3...g6 we have
reached the starting position of the Pirc Defense.} 4. Bg5 {This is one of
White's more aggressive setups. Similar to 4.Be3 White aims for rapid
Queenside development. Quite frequently, our opponent aims for Queenside
castling and intends to launch a Kingside attack. But why does White play 4.
Bg5 instead of 4.Be3? After 4.Bg5 the Bishop is more active than on e3. It
attacks our f6-Knight and we have to reckon with e4-e5 in many cases. Sounds
great for White but there are drawbacks. First of all, the Bishop might get
kicked away with ...h6 and possibly ...g5. In some cases, White needs to give
up the Bishop-pair, as we will see. A second point, compared to Be3 setups, is
the neglect of central control on d4 and c5. On e3 the Bishop helps to control
those squares, while on g5, and often h4 later, this piece is not connected to
the centre and Queenside action. A crucial point to mention is that White's
various continuations after 4...Bg7 - 5.Qd2 , 5.f4 , 5.Nf3 and 5.e5 - require
different responses. There is no 'one size fits all' approach or a 'setup' to
go for. Each line leads to different position types and needs a specific
answer.} Bg7 {A perfectly normal move, but we need to talk about it in more
detail. On move four, White has three reasonable moves of the Queen's Bishop,
@@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pp1p/3p1np1/8/3PP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0
4@@EndFEN@@ 4.Be3 , 4.Bf4 , and 4.Bg5 . These moves share some common ideas,
but also differ considerably in some ways. In our repertoire, we handle the
moves 4.Be3 and 4.Bf4 in the same way, by playing an immediate 4...a6! to
answer 5.Qd2 with 5...b5! We keep the Bishop on f8 to take the sting out of
White's Qd2 & Bh6 idea. The line @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pp1p/3p1np1/8/3PP3/
2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@ 4.Be3 Bg7?! 5.Qd2 and next Bh6
scores particularly well for White and should be avoided. The same applies for
@@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pp1p/3p1np1/8/3PP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0
4@@EndFEN@@ 4.Bf4 a6! , as White's Bh6 idea works just as well with a Bishop
on f4. Now, let's look at @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pp1p/3p1np1/8/3PP3/2N5/
PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@ 4.Bg5 should we play 4...a6 here, too?
No, this is a mistake due to 5.e5! highlighting a critical difference between
the Bishop placements. Therefore we suggest playing @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/
ppp1pp1p/3p1np1/8/3PP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@ 4.Bg5 Bg7!
but what about 5.Qd2 then? Is this a problem due to Bh6 next, just like after
@@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pp1p/3p1np1/8/3PP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0
4@@EndFEN@@ 4.Be3 Bg7?! No, because this time we can benefit from the Bishop
position on g5 by playing @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pp1p/3p1np1/8/3PP3/2N5/
PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@ 4.Bg5 Bg7 5.Qd2 h6! which stops the
exchange idea in its tracks. In the variations @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pp1p/
3p1np1/8/3PP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@ 4.Be3 and 4.Bf4 , we
play 4...a6 , which defines our pawn structure on the Queenside early on. How
do we handle our Queenside formation against @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pp1p/
3p1np1/8/3PP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@ 4.Bg5? This decision
depends on White's fifth move and needs to be decided on a case-by-case basis.
Some lines feature relatively uncommon ideas in the Pirc, involving the move ..
.d6-d5. In the Shirt & Sweet, we will focus on the sharpest moves 5.f4 , 5.e5
and White's main choice 5.Qd2 . White rarely plays 5.Nf3 when we recommend the
quirky 5...Nc6!?} 5. Qd2 {This is White's most popular choice against 4...Bg7,
played in roughly half of the games.} h6 {It is possible to play other moves
at this stage, but we like 5...h6 the most. A common approach in our
repertoire is a quick ...a6, but 5...a6 allow White to play Bh6 with a tempo
gain. After Qd2, we should stop the threat Bh6. With 5...h6 , we gain a tempo
at the cost of weakening our Kingside position. On the other hand, we win time,
and White needs to commit to a different Bishop position or take on f6. We
don't mind getting the Bishop-pair so easily, so we'll focus on the Bishop
retreats.} 6. Bh4 {White keeps the Bishop on the h4-d8 diagonal. It is
regarded as the mainline and is the only choice of 4. Bg5 expert GM S.Tiviakov.
He played it in all of his games in our database, even though White has
sensible alternatives.} O-O {Black usually goes for the Bishop-pair with ...g5
and ...Nh5, but the resulting weaknesses are severe. We prefer a different
approach: White's Bishop retreat has given up the pressure on h6. Therefore
can castle and don't need to be afraid of a quick Kingside attack. Common
ideas like Bh6 or h4-h5 are off the table.} 7. O-O-O {Active and logical.
White's primary alternative is 7.f4 but it is a transposition to
@@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pp1p/3p1np1/8/3PP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0
4@@EndFEN@@ 4.Bg5 Bg7 5.f4 O-O 6.Qd2 h6 7.Bh4 . Our reply is 7...e5! ,
intending 8.fxe5 Nxe4! More information on this line can be found via the
other, more common move order.} c6 {One of the most important moments to
remember in the whole Bg5 complex. We very rarely play ...c6 in our repertoire,
but here we need to. This time we can't play 7...a6 , due to the powerful
reply 8.e5! The pressure on the diagonal h4-d8 is annoying, and we need to
prepare a good reply to the e5-push. After 7...c6 , we gain the option to play
...Nd5 in reply to e5 and prepare our Queenside counterplay with ...b5 at the
same time. We'll examine Whites' central pawn pushes 8.f4 and 8.e5 and the
more restrained prophylactic move 8.Kb1} 8. Kb1 {A good prophylactic move for
White. The King protects a2 because this pawn is often a target after ...Qa5, .
..b5, and ...b4. After instead 8.f4 b5! or @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/pp2ppb1/
2pp1npp/8/3PP2B/2N5/PPPQ1PPP/2KR1BNR w - - 0 8@@EndFEN@@ 8.e5 Nd5! Black is
fine. Both lines show the virtues of the move 7...c6.} Qc7 {A necessary
preparation for ...b5. The immediate 8...b5 is worse due to 9.e5 , which we'd
like to respond with 9...b4 but 10.exf6 bxc3 11.fxe7 wins the house for White.
By inserting 8...Qc7 , we avoid the ...e5-pawn push for the moment and are
ready to play ...b5 next.} 9. f4 {White renews the e4-e5 threat.} b5 {Finally,
we grab some space on the Queenside. We need some counterplay, and it comes
just in time.} 10. Bxf6 {An important move to check. We are now forced to take
with the pawn, as 10...Bxf6? 11.f5! is surprisingly awkward for Black to meet.
White would continue with g4 and get a strong attack. White's alternatives to
10.Bxf6 are not dangerous, for example, 10.e5 b4! can easily backfire and turn
into an advantage for Black.} exf6 {As already mentioned: we need to recapture
with the pawn. After this move, we are in uncharted waters. The only game that
reached 10.Bxf6 continued with 10...Bxf6 After the improvement 10...exf6
Stockfish points to 11.f5 as critical. Sometimes engine evaluations are tough
to translate into human rationale, but here the point is clear. White wants to
stop ...f6-f5, which would bring our g7-Bishop back to life. We are not
'threatening' to play ...f5 right away, but it's a key idea in general. We'll
check 11.f5 , as the less direct 11.Nf3 is answered with 11...f5!} 11. f5 Nd7 {
This looks best. Our plan is ...Nd7-b6 and ultimately ...d5 to attack the base
pawn on e4.} 12. Nf3 {White can try other setups, like 12.g4 but our idea
remains the same: 12...Nb6 13.Nh3 d5! 14.exd5 b4! with sharp play.} Nb6 13. g4
b4 {All according to plan. We push away the Knight and play ...d5 next.} 14.
Ne2 d5 15. Ng3 Rb8 {Instead, taking on e4 is possible, too. After 15...Rb8 ,
the situation is complicated, and the computer evaluation about equal is not
helpful. We'll play ...a5-a4 next, while White needs to decide what to do in
the Kingside. Our King position is rather safe, due to the guardian Bishop on
g7.} *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Short & Sweet"]
[Black "The Italian Pirc (4.Bc4) #1"]
[Result "*"]
[PlyCount "26"]

1. e4 d6 {This is the starting move of the Pirc Defense. We open the c8-h3
diagonal for our light-squared Bishop, but this is not the primary purpose of
that move. By playing 1...d6 we stop White from pushing e4-e5 for the time
being. We plan to develop our Kingside by fianchettoing the dark-squared
Bishop with ...g6 and ...Bg7. The Knight usually jumps to f6, and we are ready
to castle Kingside quickly.} 2. d4 {White occupies the centre with the perfect
pawn duo on e4 and d4, a very natural move. White occasionally plays without
d4, for example by playing 2.Nc3 or 2.Bc4 . Black's Pirc setup with ...g6, ...
Bg7 and ...O-O is a good answer to these offbeat lines, too.} Nf6 {The Knight
immediately attacks the e4-pawn. This reduces White's options, compared to
playing 2...g6 or the similar @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/
RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@ 1.e4 g6 2.d4 Bg7 , which allows White to play
3.c4 amongst others. After 2...Nf6 , White's overwhelming main move is 3.Nc3
on which we will focus in the Short & Sweet.} 3. Nc3 g6 {After 3...g6 we have
reached the starting position of the Pirc Defense.} 4. Bc4 {White moves his
Kingside Bishop to an active square, pointing to f7, the weakest spot in
Black's camp. This concept is also seen in the Italian game after
@@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@
1.e4 e5 2.Nf3 Nc6 3.Bc4 , which is why we decided to call the line 'Italian
Pirc'. It seems that the line has no commonly accepted name, though. It is
recommended in the book Gambit Opening Repertoire by Eric Schiller. He calls
it the 'Short Attack', but we have only found one game played by Nigel Short
in this variation, and this happened to be a simultaneous event. Well, back to
the actual merits of the move. Playing the Bishop to the 'Italian square'
looks like a reasonable choice, but what are the drawbacks? There are two, one
tactical and one strategic. The tactical one is related to the idea ...Nxe4,
followed by d6-d5. A typical line to illustrate this idea is
@@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pp1p/3p1np1/8/2BPP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQK1NR b KQkq - 1
4@@EndFEN@@ 4...Bg7 5.Nf3 O-O 6.O-O Nxe4! 7.Nxe4 d5 , which gives us good play.
Note that ...Nxe4 should only be played after ...O-O is already on the board.
White may answer our Knight move with Bxf7+, dragging our King out in the open.
After ...O-O, the capture on f7 can be answered with ...Rxf7!, keeping our
King safe. The slight strategic drawback of the move 4.Bc4 is that in some
lines, Black manages to generate play on the dark squares, as the pinning move
...Bg4 gains strength. In connection with ...Nc6, Black gets some pressure on
d4, often establishing a Knight on this central square. In the Italian Pirc,
most lines don't require exact knowledge... but there is one exception. After
@@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pp1p/3p1np1/8/3PP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0
4@@EndFEN@@ 4.Bc4 Bg7 5.Qe2 we recommend the best move 5...Nc6 , which allows
6.e5!? leading to tactical complications. This line is fine for Black, but
it's advisable to study it and avoid getting surprised by it.} Bg7 {We play
the natural move and stay flexible. As mentioned before, 4...Nxe4? is too
early due to 5.Bxf7+ exposing our King. After 4...Bg7 , the two main paths are
5.Nf3 @@StartBracket@@which often arises after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pp1p/
3p1np1/8/3PP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@ 4.Nf3 Bg7 5.Bc4
@@EndBracket@@, and the more aggressive @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/ppp1ppbp/3p1np1/8/
2BPP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQK1NR w KQkq - 2 5@@EndFEN@@ 5.Qe2 , which forces matters
due to the immediate threat of e4-e5.} 5. Qe2 {If White avoids the classical
setup with Nf3, the move 5.Qe2 is likely the choice. White's idea is to push
his e-pawn to e5 and possibly to e6.} Nc6 {We have many alternatives, such as
castling or playing ...c6. However, 5... Nc6 is an interesting move. It points
at a drawback of the early 5. Qe2: the pawn on d4 is weak and now needs some
protection.} 6. e5 {Wait, what? Shouldn't White be worried about d4? Still,
this aggressive pawn push is the move you will most likely face in this
position. White doesn't care about d4 and instead attacks our Knight. After
the less aggressive move 6.Nf3 Black is fine with 6...Bg4 and ...e5 next,
fighting for the dark central squares.} Ng4 {We suggest 6...Ng4 , instead of
picking up the gauntlet with 6...Nxd4 . We think that 6...Ng4 is a good move,
and we suggest a new idea for Black in the main continuation. More on that
later, once we check the details. The second point is that we are sceptical
about Black's chances after 6...Nxd4 , which forces the following sequence 7.
exf6 Nxe2 8.fxg7 Rg8 9.Ngxe2 Rxg7 10.Bh6 Rg8 11.O-O-O . A fascinating line
that features a unique material balance, but we felt that it is easier to play
with White. Black's main reply is 11...Be6 , when 12.Bxe6 fxe6 13.h4 was the
line that we disliked. White still keeps the option to play f3 and place a
Knight on the secure square e4. These lines are unconventional, and you might
have a different opinion on Black's prospects If you like these positions - it
is forced after 6...Nxd4 to move 13 - you can go for 6...Nxd4 . We decided to
avoid 6...Nxd4 , also for a psychological reason. White invited this line and
likely feels at home if we accept the challenge. On the other hand, our move 6.
..Ng4 leads to entirely different positions. As a nice bonus, White now
frequently falls into a trap - let's look at the mistake 7.e6? and White's
only good move, 7.Bb5} 7. Bb5 {The only good move for White. The pawn centre
is under heavy pressure, and playing 7.Bb5 and taking on c6 next is the only
way to keep it stable. We think that an aggressive player on the White side
won't be happy with this scenario. The arising positions are objectively equal,
but White's attacking chances are diminished without the active Bishop.
Instead 7.e6? is a mistake, as 7...Nxd4! 8.Qxg4 Nxc2+ is winning for Black.}
O-O 8. Bxc6 {No choice for White. The pawn on d4 was hanging, and e5 was
attacked multiple times.} bxc6 {Now White has to start with 9.h3 . The natural
move 9.Nf3 is a mistake.} 9. h3 Nh6 10. Nf3 {White has successfully navigated
all the pitfalls and now reached this position. We suggest a new move for
Black now.} Qd7 {Yes, this looks very odd at first, but there is a method to
the madness. The concept is best explained by looking at the move 10...f6 .
This move is very logical, as the e5-pawn hampers Black's position. If we
manage to play ...f6 and White needs to take on f6 or d6, we have accomplished
a lot. Removing the e5-pawn and, on a perfect day, the d4-pawn is the dream
scenario for our Bishops. So, why not 10...f6 , then? There are two issues
with the move. The first, less problematic one, is 11.exf6 exf6 12.Qc4+ ,
which wins a pawn for White. Black has some compensation, so this wouldn't be
a show stopper The real issue is @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/p1p1p1bp/2pp1ppn/4P3/3P4/
2N2N1P/PPP1QPP1/R1B1K2R w KQ - 0 11@@EndFEN@@ 11.e6!? , which is tough to play
for Black. The h6-Knight is stranded, and it is not clear how to organize the
forces. Instead of 10...f6 , the move 10...Nf5 came into consideration. But
White replies 11.Bf4 and retains the option to castle Queenside. By now, you
probably have guessed the intention of 10...Qd7!? . We want to play ...f6 or ..
.Nf5 at the right moment, without the worries, just described. The Queen looks
odd on d7, but hang on: it has an active prospect that is not so obvious at
the moment. Our move is a novelty, so what replies to check? We think 10.O-O
and 10.Bf4 makes the most sense, so we'll examine these moves.} 11. O-O {
Against 11.Bf4 the pawn break 11...f6 is very effective. White doesn't have
the reply 12.e6 now and needs to take.} Nf5 {After @@StartFEN@@r1b2rk1/
p1pqppbp/2pp2pn/4P3/3P4/2N2N1P/PPP1QPP1/R1B1K2R w KQ - 3 11@@EndFEN@@ 11.O-O ,
the second idea of ...Qd7 is revealed. The Knight move is a lot stronger than
11...f6 . Our intention is ...c5 next, followed by ...Bb7 and ...Qc6. at the
cost of a pawn, our Bishops spring to life. Let's have a look at this idea.}
12. Re1 {White shouldn't lash out with 12.g4?! the simple reply 12...Nh6 is
good enough when ...Nxg4 is a dangerous idea.} c5 13. dxc5 {The best move. 13.
d5? Nd4! is a huge mistake and @@StartFEN@@r1b2rk1/p1pqppbp/3p2p1/2p1Pn2/3P4/
2N2N1P/PPP1QPP1/R1B1R1K1 w - - 0 13@@EndFEN@@ 13.exd6 cxd4! 14.dxe7 Re8 is
better for Black, too.} Bb7 {Our Bishop on b7 is a great piece, ruling on the
long diagonal. We have excellent play for the pawn and good chances to grab
the initiative. The Queen coming to c6 will already set up the threat ...Nd4 -
not easy for White to handle. To conclude the analysis: we think that 6... Ng4
is a good practical choice for Black. We have some new active ideas up our
sleeve and don't play into unconventional positions that give White the
initiative, as 6... Nxd4 does.} *

