tactical and one strategic. The tactical one is related to the idea ...Nxe4,
followed by d6-d5. A typical line to illustrate this idea is
@@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pp1p/3p1np1/8/2BPP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQK1NR b KQkq - 1
4@@EndFEN@@ 4...Bg7 5.Nf3 O-O 6.O-O Nxe4! 7.Nxe4 d5 , which gives us good play.
Note that ...Nxe4 should only be played after ...O-O is already on the board.
White may answer our Knight move with Bxf7+, dragging our King out in the open.
After ...O-O, the capture on f7 can be answered with ...Rxf7!, keeping our
King safe. The slight strategic drawback of the move 4.Bc4 is that in some
lines, Black manages to generate play on the dark squares, as the pinning move
...Bg4 gains strength. In connection with ...Nc6, Black gets some pressure on
d4, often establishing a Knight on this central square. In the Italian Pirc,
most lines don't require exact knowledge... but there is one exception. After
@@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pp1p/3p1np1/8/3PP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0
4@@EndFEN@@ 4.Bc4 Bg7 5.Qe2 we recommend the best move 5...Nc6 , which allows
6.e5!? leading to tactical complications. This line is fine for Black, but
it's advisable to study it and avoid getting surprised by it.} Bg7 {We play
the natural move and stay flexible. As mentioned before, 4...Nxe4? is too
early due to 5.Bxf7+ exposing our King. After 4...Bg7 , the two main paths are
5.Nf3 @@StartBracket@@which often arises after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pp1p/
3p1np1/8/3PP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@ 4.Nf3 Bg7 5.Bc4
@@EndBracket@@, and the more aggressive @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/ppp1ppbp/3p1np1/8/
2BPP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQK1NR w KQkq - 2 5@@EndFEN@@ 5.Qe2 , which forces matters
due to the immediate threat of e4-e5.} 5. Nf3 {A very natural move. This
position frequently arises after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pp1p/3p1np1/8/3PP3/
2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@ 4.Nf3 Bg7 5.Bc4 , even more often
than via @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pp1p/3p1np1/8/3PP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR w
KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@ 4.Bc4 .} O-O {We castle and protect f7 at the same time.
Now the idea ...Nxe4!? is much more interesting than before because Bxf7+ can
be answered with ...Rxf7. Now, White has got many options on how to continue
development. However, we can easily distinguish between two scenarios: White
either allows ...Nxe4 or not. If White is aware of the idea, then 6.Qe2 or 6.
Bb3 comes into consideration. Against these moves, we play for control of the
dark squares with 6...Bg4 . More common are 6.O-O , 6.h3 , or 6.Bg5 when we
are happy to take on e4. For the purpose of the Short & Sweet, we'll examine
the most played move 6.O-O} 6. O-O {White castles as well, which looks natural
and is by far the most popular move. Now we like to attack White's centre. We
have two options to reach our goal. At the moment, White controls d5
@@StartBracket@@with Nc3, Bc4, and pawn on e4 @@EndBracket@@, but we have the
already mentioned tactical shot Nxe4 followed by d6-d5 to change this
situation. We reach easy equality and often have some structural benefits,
such as two central pawns or a pair of Bishops. Other moves are possible, but
we think ...Nxe4 is an opportunity we should take.} Nxe4 {We already talked
about this idea. Taking on e4 is Black's principled choice and our suggestion.
Now White has two moves that lead to different scenarios. In both cases, Black
gets fair chances and interesting positions to play.} 7. Nxe4 {This is played
most of the time. White wants to keep his Bishop-pair. After 7.Bxf7+ Rxf7 8.
Nxe4 h6! White gives up the Bishop-pair and weakens the light squares around
our King. However, this also opens the f-file for our Rook and grants Black an
extra centre pawn, as White traded e-pawn for f-pawn. All things considered,
this means Black should be in great shape in the long run, while we need to be
careful due to the possibly precarious King position.} d5 8. Bd3 dxe4 9. Bxe4 {
After some forced moves, we reach the current position. We now need to find
squares for our Queenside pieces. We would also like to attack White's central
d4-pawn. To do so, we could either try to push ...c5 or ...e5. It's logical to
use our c5-pawn to keep the central e-pawn. We prepare this push with Nd7.} Nd7
{The Knight is flexible on d7 and can either go to c5 or f6 later on. We can
decide later on what to do with our Bishop. We can fianchetto it, or post it
somewhere on the diagonal c8-h3, likely g4 or e6. At the moment, it does an
excellent job in protecting the pawn on b7, which is under the attack of
White's e4-Bishop. Next on the agenda is attacking the d4-pawn.} 10. c3 {White
overprotects his d4-pawn and tries to blunt our g7-Bishop. This is the best
and by far most popular move.} c5 {Here 10...e5 is a good alternative, but
attacking d4 with the c-pawn is more enterprising. Let's see what happens if
White tries to continue with a normal-looking development move.} 11. Bg5 cxd4
12. Nxd4 {This avoids an IQP and is White's best.} Qb6 {Black has some good
alternatives here, but this move is the most straightforward solution. We get
out of the annoying vis-a-vis to White's Bg5 and attack White's b-pawn. This
directly prepares ...e5 and promises a good game. Please note that White can't
win a pawn by playing 13.Bxe7 after 13...Re8 , both Bishops are attacked on
the e-file.} *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Short & Sweet"]
[Black "The solid Fianchetto (4.g3)"]
[Result "*"]
[PlyCount "28"]

1. e4 d6 {This is the starting move of the Pirc Defense. We open the c8-h3
diagonal for our light-squared Bishop, but this is not the primary purpose of
that move. By playing 1...d6 we stop White from pushing e4-e5 for the time
being. We plan to develop our Kingside by fianchettoing the dark-squared
Bishop with ...g6 and ...Bg7. The Knight usually jumps to f6, and we are ready
to castle Kingside quickly.} 2. d4 {White occupies the centre with the perfect
pawn duo on e4 and d4, a very natural move. White occasionally plays without
d4, for example by playing 2.Nc3 or 2.Bc4 . Black's Pirc setup with ...g6, ...
Bg7 and ...O-O is a good answer to these offbeat lines, too.} Nf6 {The Knight
immediately attacks the e4-pawn. This reduces White's options, compared to
playing 2...g6 or the similar @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/
RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@ 1.e4 g6 2.d4 Bg7 , which allows White to play
3.c4 amongst others. After 2...Nf6 , White's overwhelming main move is 3.Nc3
on which we will focus in the Short & Sweet.} 3. Nc3 g6 {After 3...g6 we have
reached the starting position of the Pirc Defense.} 4. g3 {This move
introduces the Fianchetto Variation. By playing 4.g3 , White signals that he
is not going for a furious attack on our King. White instead wants to build up
a solid position and control the game. It's a good variation for the type of
White player who likes a positional game with relatively low risk. White's
most common way to develop is Bg2, Nge2, O-O, h3, Be3 and Qd2. In many cases,
White wants to gain space on the Kingside after castling by playing f4, g4,
and possibly f4-f5 or g4-g5 later on. The Bishop on g2 will protect the
important e4-pawn and discourages an advance of our b-pawn due to a possible
e4-e5 push. Therefore we don't play for a Queenside expansion but prefer to
play in the centre. Our approach is playing a quick ...e5, followed by ...exd4.
We open the long diagonal for our Bishop and start counterplay against the
e4-pawn, based on ...Re8.} Bg7 {There is no need for us to be tricky regarding
move order nuances. We continue with our development and play the natural move.
} 5. Bg2 O-O {We keep on developing and bring our King to a safer position.
Now White's main choice is between two development options for the King's
Knight. The most popular move is 6.Nge2 , but 6.Nf3 is possible, too. Against
6.Nge2 we can immediately play 6...e5 , while after the rare
@@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/ppp1ppbp/3p1np1/8/3PP3/2N3P1/PPP2PBP/R1BQK1NR w KQ - 3
6@@EndFEN@@ 6.Nf3 we suggest starting with 6...Nc6 to prepare ...e5 next.} 6.
Nge2 {This is the main move in this variation by far. White avoids a possible
pin after 6.Nf3 Bg4 @@StartBracket@@we don't recommend this,
though@@EndBracket@@ and keeps the e4-pawn covered. Later on, White is also
able to use the f-pawn in some lines. This strategy is very effective against
passive play, against setups with ...c6 and ...Nbd7, for example. We advise
playing more actively and put pressure on White's centre.} e5 {White does not
have any control over the e5-square, so we don't need to prepare for this move.
After @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/ppp1ppbp/3p1np1/8/3PP3/2N3P1/PPP2PBP/R1BQK1NR w KQ
- 3 6@@EndFEN@@ 6.Nf3 , we need to play ...Nc6 first, which is unnecessary
here.} 7. h3 {The small pawn move is White's most popular choice. Be3 is part
of the setup, and White needs to stop ...Ng4. Against 7.O-O we'd also take on
d4, leading to the same positions.} exd4 8. Nxd4 Re8 9. O-O Bd7 {We advise
starting with 9...Bd7 . Instead, 9...Nc6 is not a mistake, but there is no
upside in allowing 10.Nxc6 bxc6 .} 10. Be3 {White played h3 to prepare this
move. After 10.Re1 Nc6 White's most logical move is 11.Be3 , which transposes
to @@StartFEN@@rn1qr1k1/pppb1pbp/3p1np1/8/3NP3/2N3PP/PPP2PB1/R1BQ1RK1 w - - 3
10@@EndFEN@@ 10.Be3 Nc6 11.Re1 , the mainline. White has tried
@@StartFEN@@rn1qr1k1/pppb1pbp/3p1np1/8/3NP3/2N3PP/PPP2PB1/R1BQ1RK1 w - - 3
10@@EndFEN@@ 10.Bg5 , but 10...Nc6 11.Nde2 h6 just sends the Bishop back to e3.
} Nc6 {Black's position looks quite well organized. We have developed all
minor pieces and put some pressure on e4. Our next step, in most cases, is to
trade on d4 and play ...c5 and ...Bc6 next. White's most popular move is 11.
Re1 , after which we will employ the described plan. A different scenario
arises after 11.Nde2 , which stops the trade on d4. This is welcome, though -
we have a great reply with 11...b5!? , generating good counterplay on the
Queenside.} 11. Re1 {This is played most of the time. White lends some extra
protection to the e4-pawn and covers the Bishop on e3, which is often
necessary to continue with f4. We have examined 11.f4? Nxe4! , illustrating
the dangers for White.} Nxd4 {We regard this as the easiest way to equalize.}
12. Bxd4 c5 {This turns our d-pawn into a backward pawn. In return, we put a
lot of pressure on the e4-pawn with ...Bc6 next and have control over some
important dark squares in the centre. Like in some Sicilian Defense lines,
White never manages to get serious pressure on the d-pawn, so this static
weakness is not concerning.} 13. Be3 {White wants to keep the Bishop-pair,
which is understandable. After 13.Bxf6 , our g7-Bishop would rule the dark
squares. We have examined @@StartFEN@@r2qr1k1/pppb1pbp/2np1np1/8/3NP3/2N1B1PP/
PPP2PB1/R2Q1RK1 w - - 5 11@@EndFEN@@ 11.Qd2 Nxd4 12.Bxd4 c5 13.Bxf6 briefly,
which is a similar story.} Bc6 {Our light-squared Bishop finds a good square
and puts pressure on White's e4-pawn.} 14. Qd3 {White also plays 14.Bf4
frequently, which can also be answered with 14...Re6 . Our Rook does an
excellent job on e6, protecting d6 and attacking e4 simultaneously. The game
is very similar to our mainline 14.Qd3} Re6 {After 14...Re6 Black nicely
manages to combine defending the d-pawn with counterplay against e4. With ...
Qe7 or ...Qe8 you can increase the pressure on White's pawn next.} *

