1. e4 d6 {This is the starting move of the Pirc Defense. We open the c8-h3
diagonal for our light-squared Bishop, but this is not the primary purpose of
that move. By playing 1...d6 we stop White from pushing e4-e5 for the time
being. We plan to develop our Kingside by fianchettoing the dark-squared
Bishop with ...g6 and ...Bg7. The Knight usually jumps to f6, and we are ready
to castle Kingside quickly.} 2. d4 {White occupies the centre with the perfect
pawn duo on e4 and d4, a very natural move. White occasionally plays without
d4, for example by playing 2.Nc3 or 2.Bc4 . Black's Pirc setup with ...g6, ...
Bg7 and ...O-O is a good answer to these offbeat lines, too.} Nf6 {The Knight
immediately attacks the e4-pawn. This reduces White's options, compared to
playing 2...g6 or the similar @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/
RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@ 1.e4 g6 2.d4 Bg7 , which allows White to play
3.c4 amongst others. After 2...Nf6 , White's overwhelming main move is 3.Nc3
on which we will focus in the Short & Sweet.} 3. Nc3 g6 {After 3...g6 we have
reached the starting position of the Pirc Defense.} 4. Be2 {This move does not
look very aggressive at first, but looks can be deceiving. Just wait for the
next move!} Bg7 {No surprise at this point.} 5. h4 {Harry! Attacking ...g6
with h4 is all the rage in modern Chess, but this line has a long history.
There are plenty of games from the early days of the Pirc, dating back to the
1950s and 1960s. Black's main choice after 5.h4 is whether to allow h4-h5 or
not.} h5 {'No h5! for you!' We advise stopping the h-pawn in its tracks. Black
has two good moves after 5. h4. The choice is limited, as slow moves don't cut
it after the aggressive h-pawn thrust. Our common theme to play ...Nc6 or ...
a6 does not work here. It is simply too slow. We must stop the further advance
of White's h-pawn by playing 5...h5 @@StartBracket@@our choice@@EndBracket@@
or start a counter-attack immediately by playing 5...c5 . If you like to
expand your repertoire or want to analyze an alternative, the c-pawn move is
the only worthwhile attempt to deviate. We prefer 5...h5 because we think the
resulting positions are easier to handle. After 5...c5 6.dxc5 Qa5 White has
multiple options that require some precision. On the other hand, 5...h5 is
less dependent on concrete memorization and more of a strategic nature. The
drawback of 5...h5 is that we lose some time and also weaken our Kingside
position. White might play g2-g4 later on, to open lines at the Kingside, but
this is not easy to accomplish. A more common scenario is reached when White
uses the g5-square for his pieces. It's hard to get rid of them because ...h6
is out of the picture, and ...f6 is rarely an option. Let's check some
concrete lines now. A common theme is that we are not castling quickly, but
rather seek counterplay through ...Nc6 and/or ...a6 as we do in many other
lines in this repertoire. A notable exception is a quick O-O by White, when we
don't mind placing our King on the Kingside, too.} 6. Bg5 {This is the most
popular move. White develops his dark-squared Bishop and prepares Queenside
castling. In the main course, we also analyze some alternatives for White,
most importantly 6.Nh3 which we suggest answering with 6...Bxh3 7.Rxh3 Nc6 .}
a6 {A rare move, but in the spirit of our repertoire. Similar to the positions
that arise after 4. Be3, we react with a preparation of a Queenside attack.} 7.
Qd2 {White sticks to his plan to castle Queenside. As mentioned, 6... a6 is
rare, so we don't have many game samples to rely on. The Queen move is very
logical, though, and therefore the one we'll explore a bit.} b5 {We don't
hesitate with our Queenside counterplay. We threaten to play b4, which attacks
the sole defender of the e4-pawn.} 8. f3 {White protects e4 and also possibly
prepares a g2-g4 pawn push.} Nbd7 {Black has a range of good moves, like 8...
Nc6 or 8...c6 , but this is a tempting option. 8...Nbd7 prepare ...c5 next. As
mentioned before, there is no established 'theory' after move six, so there is
scope for creative play. It's more of a 'game to play' than 'theory to know'.}
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Short & Sweet"]
[Black "Introduction"]
[Result "*"]
[PlyCount "1"]

1. -- {Hello and Welcome to Short & Sweet: Pirc Defense. Let's talk about the
nature and history of the Pirc Defense for a moment. The Pirc Defense is not a
'classical' Opening. What is the definition of 'classical' in chess? The
classical values go back to the beginning of chess as a subject of systematic
research. Concepts like 'controlling the centre with pawns', 'developing
pieces quickly', 'play for quick castling', 'keep a sound pawn structure' were
developed by the greats of the past; names like Steinitz or Tarrasch come to
mind. While most of the mentioned values are present in the Pirc, one crucial
point is neglected: controlling the centre with pawns. Black is happily
allowing White to occupy the centre with the perfect pawn duo e4 & d4, which
quickly can be supplemented with an additional pawn on f4 if White wishes to
do so. Giving the opponent that much leeway in the centre was frowned upon and
even believed to be a foolish endeavour for a long time. In the 1920s, when
openings like the Nimzo-Indian and the Grünfeld already had acquired some
credibility, answering 1.e4 with 1...d6 or 1...g6 was considered a mistake. In
his classic book about the New York Tournament 1924, Alekhine called ...g6 a
joke opening and attached a question mark to the move. At the time, these ...
d6/...g6 Defenses to e4 were usually called Old Indian. About two decades
later, after the Second World War, this setup was adopted by two players. The
first one was GM Vasja Pirc, a multiple champion of Yugoslavia, the second one
was Anatoli Ufimzew, a strong Soviet master. Ufimzew never was allowed to play
outside of the Soviet Union - he surely would have earned the GM title
otherwise. These two players, completely independent from one another,
analyzed and played the opening frequently. Nowadays, the name 'Pirc Defense'
is commonly accepted for the subject of our course, the sequence
@@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@
1.e4 d6 2.d4 Nf6 3.Nc3 g6 . In the past, the name 'Pirc-Ufimtsev Defense' or
even just 'Ufimzev Defense' was also frequently used. We decided to use 'Pirc
Defense', as this name is by far the commonly accepted one. Pirc and Ufimtsev
introduced and refined the opening, which quickly gained momentum in the 1950s
and 1960s. Legendary players and World Champions like Smyslov, Botvinnik, and
Bobby Fischer played the Pirc, in Fischer's case even in the World
Championship Match against Spassky. In modern times, the Pirc has attracted
ambitious players like Svidler, Mamedyarov, and Morozevich. Many strong
players use it as an occasional weapon to fight for a win, including World
Champion Magnus Carlsen. So, what are some key concepts of the Pirc? - Black
does not immediately place a pawn in the centre but prefers to attack White's
pawn centre later. Black has many ways to do that, for example, with ...e7-e5
or ...c7-c5. Black might even wait with such a strike even longer and first
expand on the Queenside with ...b5. Black has many options and possible pawn
structures to choose from. - Black's play may provoke White to be overly
aggressive, which can lead to overextension. White's space advantage can
backfire, in particular, if White has advanced pawns around their King. - The
struggle between White's centre and Black trying to fight it can often lead to
very concrete, tactical play. Black needs to play actively. Otherwise, White's
space might be a decisive factor. We have selected lines that go for sharp
counterplay and pose problems for our opponent. Passive play is a recipe for
disaster in the Pirc. - The Pirc is less explored compared to more frequently
played main lines. It is possible to find new ideas early on, which is more
difficult in mainstream openings. - On the non-professional level, White often
has no preparation against the Pirc. White players usually focus on the most
popular moves @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq -
0 1@@EndFEN@@ 1.e4 e5 , 1...c5 , 1...c6 and 1...e6 but neglect other openings.
Against the Pirc, White has no widely known 'spoilsport' option. There is no
'Exchange Variation' or a System like the Alapin in the Sicilian, making the
Pirc an excellent practical weapon to play for a win. The drawing percentage
in the Pirc is low. - Move orders can be tricky to master for both sides. We
have selected lines that share common ideas, like an early ...a6 and ...Nc6.
This reduces the danger of accidentally entering a line that you have not
prepared. Now, let's have a look at some essential variations to get you
started with the Pirc!} *

